The ČSSD in Prague doesn't know Voldemort or the bakery.
The new ČSSD councillors in the capital will have to overcome, it seems, the obvious language barriers so that the Prague City Council and City Council members can understand their newly-found SDG colleagues.
The Aktuálně.cz period "examined" the members of the new ČSSD Council to check their knowledge of the slang-marked language that has emerged in the Council in recent years, when the current members of the coalition governed Prague.
The coded dictionary that used the political flower and cream of Prague during the previous period, by Mayor Pavel Bém, includes some of the metropolis' best-known characters, situations and causes.
Surprisingly, new council members have been found to have little understanding of these familiar concepts.
At least, that's what they say.
"Who is Voldemort?"
"I don't know, really".
"I am rather a newcomer to Prague politics", said culture councillor Lukáš Kaucký during the terminology exam for "college".
And as far as the veteran politician is concerned, Karel Březina reacted the same.
You may be familiar with the concept of a golf hole.
"It's probably the only expression of all the ones you asked me that I use now and then".
"Otherwise, I don't usually use slang".
From the glossary, the definitions of which were published by Aktuálně.cz in June before the SDG voting congress, the editorial board selected six examples, in particular those that are particularly relevant to the municipal authorities in Prague.
The socialists had to explain the concepts "Voldemort", "largest golf hole in Prague", "going to the bakery", "bull neck", "treason of the capital" and "armor".
Three councillors agreed to take the test and a fourth, Antonín Weinert, who will be responsible for education in Prague in the future, initially agreed but did not pick up the phone again.
The fifth councillor, Petr Dolínek, refused to do it directly.
"I don't get involved in these things, nor do I value how civic Democrats have fun".
"What does matter to me is how we will understand each other in the execution of our programmes", he said.
As has been seen, the councillor Lukáš Kaucký would have allegedly not realized that the previous title is an expression about an influential businessman and a friend of the former mayor of Bém, Roman Janoušek.
Kaucký doesn't know the word "Voldemort"; the only term he got right in the exam is "the biggest golf hole in Prague".
"It's the Blanka tunnel", says Kaucký, who immediately adds: "But I know more from the news".
"I'm gonna have to sign up for a language course", he jokes.
Karel Březina is not the only one who recognizes the Blanka tunnel on the golf hole, but also the Environmental Councillor Lukáš Plachý.
Afterwards, both social democrats know who Voldemort really is and Lukáš Plachý even knows where to find that character; he also suspects the meaning of "going to the bakery".
"I think it means going to a company in Prague"; soon Plachý learns that this is the headquarters of Janoušek's companies.
Like Březina, he indicates that such knowledge he obtained from the news, but that he does not use such a vocabulary.
According to the test participants, no such familiar glossary of colloquial terms exists among social democrats.
"I asked my colleagues, but it really doesn't seem like we have anything in common".
"Rather, we use nicknames among ourselves, sometimes abbreviations or word games with names", says ČSSD Prague chairman Petr Hulínský, whose party mates call her Hulda.
"In school I was called Bříza, but I don't know if my classmates call me that", confesses his own nickname Karel Březina.
The newspaper Aktuálně.cz tested the name and it works.
To his party comrades, Weinert is Děda (similar to "boy") or, less friendly, Dědek ("old man"), the representative Miroslav Poche, with whom he was associated before the election during the party's sponsorship deception, receives the nickname "Igráček" ("playmobil") by some of his comrades.
Nicknames are also the only expressions that the Social Democrats tolerate in speech within the party.
Hulínský does not like to be called Hulda, but Aktuálně.cz newspaper discovered even other nicknames for this Prague president.
"The Doctor of the Rights of the Bat" apparently remembers that Petr Hulínský obtained his doctorate in law at the Bratislava Police Academy.
The government wants to limit the torture of "witches", as published in a brochure
Women considered witches in Burkina Faso share certain characteristics.
They are usually of advanced age, unable to work, for example, for health reasons, single and childless.
Women who "become" witches are sent to a secluded area, so that they do not harm the rest of the village.
"Men seldom suffer such a fate".
"Nor are healthy young women isolated, because they help with the work and have children", explains a nun who, in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso, works in a special residence for more than a hundred women expelled from their communities.
The local government has decided to oppose this unusual "social measure".
He issued an informational pamphlet that should help prevent witch hunts.
This has a downside, though.
"More than 70 percent of adults in Burkina Faso are illiterate", warns the newspaper Die Standard about the disadvantages of written education.
Charges of witchcraft are also common in other African countries.
In Ghana, a neighbouring country of Burkina Faso, Ammy Hemmah, 72, died last week when she was tortured, covered with gasoline and burned by three women and two men.
The news came on the BBC.
The authors claim that it was due to an unfortunate combination of circumstances.
According to his version, the woman caught fire in the oil used for ritual anointing.
It caught fire when the group wanted to "exorcise the evil spirits" from the woman.
Isolation of "witches" is supported by people of all educational levels.
"Soul-eaters have always been a danger", said a 42-year-old businessman in Burkina Faso, quoted in the newspaper Der Standard.
While in Burkina Faso the government is trying to quell the witch hunt, in Gambia last year the president was still involved.
"Gambian President Jammeh, after the death of his aunt, launched a massive witch hunt that allegedly had been linked to her death and had attempted to kill the president himself using black magic".
"To help him, he brought in shamans from nearby Guinea who, protected by police, military and the president's personal escort, took by force randomly selected men and women from the Gambian villages to the president's property in Kanilai", Amnesty International said in its report.
At the farm, the arrested people had to drink a potion of herbs with hallucinogenic effects that, in addition, caused intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of the arrested did not survive the stay at the estate.
After international pressure, they finally released about a thousand people detained.
Bakala tenant: heating with coal stoves and signing a higher rent
The man, a hardened elderly man, walked through the doors of the customer service center of the RPG Byty company of "coal magnate" Zdeňek Bakala, the largest private owner of rental flats in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he carried some documents with the new three-story lease contracts: his, his daughter's and his son, who is serving his sentence.
The three of them just got caught up in the rent liberalization.
Instead of 3,500 CZK a month, the child will pay from next year onwards 4,100 CZK for a two-room flat with a separate second-class kitchen.
"Moreover, it has no hot water and the heating is based on a solid fuel boiler", the man points to his son's new contract, on which he has full powers.
"But I signed it", he explains, half angry, half resigned.
The civil association BytyOKD.cz, which called the new rental conditions "incorrect and indecent", recommends that tenants not sign new contracts and wait until December 7, when it will publish a guide on how to proceed in these cases.
But man only makes a fuss.
"Each one says one thing", he says with a bad face.
Ostrava is becoming a great testing ground for liberalisation.
After the New Year, this will happen to the vast majority of apartments which in the Czech Republic were previously rented under regulation.
So Aktuálně.cz decided to visit the "laboratory" in person.
The RPG mining waiting room is one of four in Ostrava and, on Tuesday at nine, it was already full.
Right by the doors are the security guards and next to them a number machine.
"Rent 2011", you can read it on a bright button on your touch screen.
When you press it, a piece of paper with a number comes out of the machine.
It takes almost no time to read "157" and the number is already on the big screen at the top of the room.
In a second, you'll be in line.
Soon after, an elderly couple arrives to ask questions, but the crowd in the room is not here for the new rentals.
Most people come to solve common problems, as in the past: claims for repairs, insurance matters and the like.
The letters with the new lease contracts will arrive in Ostrava to the mailboxes of the tenants of most of the 44,000 apartments belonging to RPG around mid-November.
RPG Byty proposes in the letters a rent increase of between 15 and 38%.
On 18 November a special window opens in the customer service centre for new rentals.
"It's been working for a week, so it's starting", respond, after a brief hesitation, the workers who are in it when the client presents himself as a journalist.
Liberalisation and the former miners' flats of Bakala are the most sensitive issues in the area.
Before the elections, they were already treated loud and clear by the Ostrava-born deputy speaker of Parliament, Lubomír Zaorálek, of the ČSSD, and now they are continuously appearing in local newspapers.
"Twenty years later, I want a new floor".
"They didn't even change my damn bathroom dish", says the man mentioned at the outset.
According to the workers, for the time being they come mostly retired to check if they get a discount on rent if they sign on time, as promised by the special offer of RPG.
The remaining tenants who sign the new lease before December 15 will also receive half the discount on the February rent.
However, the window of "mining liberalization" certainly fails to dispel the avalanche of doubts.
"Of the 360 customers who were here yesterday, only about forty or fifty people asked for rent in 2011", the window clerk estimates.
Meanwhile, RPG proposes on its website and boards to hold individual meetings on contracts when necessary.
If the two parties cannot reach an agreement on the rent, an independent judge must decide the matter.
"This is not a threat, but information about the only possible and fully lawful way forward", warns RPG on its pages.
"No one is going to be judged here", says one of the employees of RPG Byty and a man on the street in front of the customer service centre agrees, at least in part.
"I receive a pension of 13,000 and have 5,000 left for food; I have no means to go to court", he says.
But immediately, the employee sows doubt.
"We'll see about that".
"Mr. Zaorálek warns them in the media not to sign, so maybe people will wait", he says.
Rental regulation will cease to exist in most of the Czech Republic at the beginning of 2011 and, according to RPG Byty, its increase is an economic necessity.
"The current rents still do not even cover the amounts necessary for the maintenance of the community fund", recalls Pavel Klimeš, director of the residential portfolio of the company RPG Byty, who adds that the neglected state of the community fund that angers tenants is, for the owners, the main reason for increasing the rent.
While during the five years between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able to invest in apartments with rent four billion, in the four years from 2011 to 2014 the figure will increase to 5.200 million.
The large screen hanging from the ceiling, in front of the waiting room seats, now repeats some data highlighted in red.
'The increase in rents in 2011 by 15% and less applies to 31,200 apartments, i.e. more than 90% of RPG properties.'
"In addition, it will always be a maximum of 7.50 CZK per square meter per month", the screen says.
Only increased by 38% the rent of 400 floors of the RPG portfolio.
'In such cases, this is an increase from extremely low amounts of 19,66 crowns per square metre,' RPG says.
At 2,600 apartments, the rent will remain unchanged next year.
RPG Byty promises that the liberalization will not affect rents suddenly, but will scale up between four and eight years.
It also adds the following commitment: the company will invest all the money from the rent increase (see chart) back into the flats, mainly in savings on heating: new windows and heating.
Priority will be given to people who sign the rent increase agreement.
Architects have understood that offices also need daycare.
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
No one would think that it also hides a small nursery with everything that is typical of such facilities: colorful walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, children of Arch.Design employees can come to it.
The architectural project company Arch.Design, from whose studio many well-known buildings in Brno came, thought from the first sketches of the building Avriopoint to include a space for its mini-nursery.
The company employs about 90 people, mainly in the baby boom era and wanted to allow architects and designers to return to work soon after maternity.
Along with the possibility of a reduced working time, daycare is one of the benefits that Arch.Design offers its employees as part of its social programme.
Women builders and architects are thus able to combine a demanding job with childcare.
The mini-nursery was an idea of the Arch.Designu employees themselves and, with the support of management, they managed to secure funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company's day care is financed by the European Social Fund under the Operational Programme for Human Resources and Employment and the Czech State budget.
The financing provided (a grant of over CZK 2.8 million) enabled them to purchase the equipment and, after two years, to hire qualified staff and services.
When the funding is exhausted (two years), Arch.Design is obliged to keep the mini-nursery running with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project took one year and the application for funding was supported by Economy Rating.
The children are cared for by qualified staff, and a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education are present all day to care for them.
Since it is a "mini-nursery", it can only accommodate a maximum of five children at a time, although with shifts they come more during the day.
The operation of the daycare is flexible to suit the needs of parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use the daycare, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although the programme is individual in nature, the content of the programme is comparable to that of the regular preschool.
It is not only a place for children to play, but also a place for them to receive quality education: from basic learning to school preparation, including English.
The classroom has not only toys and board games, but also a computer for the children.
The presence of young children in the company itself creates a friendly and positive atmosphere.
Parents can go to see their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up children late from school when they are away from their workplace.
This way, parents are more productive while working.
Not surprisingly, this naturally creates a relationship of loyalty between the worker and his employer.
Arch.Design is thus among the signature companies that offer a major advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, in short, this programme has strengthened the marketing of personnel.
The house of bones still fascinates after 100 years.
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs look like the column of a dinosaur, and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Because of its skeleton-like shape, the locals nicknamed it "the house of bones".
Its organic forms, striking colors, the novel use of stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade reminiscent of scales and the ubiquitous gently curved lines, all are typical of Antoni Gaudí's secession.
The front of the house plays with dreamlike lines, delicate colors and textures drawn from nature and wildlife.
Paying closer attention, you notice a certain geometry, rhythm and carefully thought out order.
At night, the entire facade of the house looks even more impressive, as it is illuminated in such a way that the brightness of the colors is enhanced.
Snake and the twist of forms continues to amaze us inside as well.
The wavy wood copies the window frames, railings, door ornaments, viewpoints, and signs.
The Batlló House, located in the Eixample district at number 43 of the lively Passeig de Gracia shopping street, was built after the remodeling of an 1877 house by architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on tearing down the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea of a new and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Batlló House, made up of several apartments, was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
The architect Josep María Jujol collaborated on the design.
In fact, in his plans for the project came up decorations for the representative apartment of the property owner and the mosaics used on the facade.
Other creators and artists also work on the facade.
The collaboration in the proposals of the Batlló House was the beginning of Jujol's successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of the Casa Milá and the Güell park of Gaudí, where other pieces of it are located.
Because of its organic shape, the locals soon after its completion nicknamed it "the house of bones".
Others, because of the specific mechanism of opening the windows, began to call it "the house of yawning".
It is also said that, at the top of the building, the sword of St. George, patron saint of Catalonia, appears.
Other sculptural elements of the building conceal religious motifs.
Gaudí designed a unique system for the time of central heating in the house with ventilation vents and typical chimneys.
It may be strange to see its 45-degree incline.
During construction, Gaudí did not respect the building codes of the time at all and was not influenced by them.
Nevertheless, the construction was given the necessary permit from the outset, although the information on the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later, when it was completed, the city council was so impressed with the result that it asked for it to be corrected.
He was bothered, for example, that the construction included columns even up to the public sidewalk.
The arrangements were never made, rather the opposite: just fifteen days after the request of the city council, Josep Batlló applied for (and obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
The owners have moved into the lower floors.
In the second floor gallery was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The six-story house is completely traversed by a stairway leading to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of space connection.
The common area can be fully connected by opening the doors of the rooms and a larger group can communicate in this way without problems, without giving up the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
The house, with Gaudí's reconstruction, not only got a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
Also impressive is Gaudí's play with light, white and blue tiles covering the inner courtyard and skylights.
The two-color game brings maximum light to every floor of the house.
It was based simply on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which, on the contrary, absorb sunlight.
Anyone can visit the Batlló House, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and most fully furnished apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that it is a very profitable business and expanded the visits to the common area and the buardilla, including the roof terrace.
The price of admission to the monument is not insignificant, reaching 16,50 euros, although students, pensioners and tourist card holders get a 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the price of admission to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
