How to choose mattress and top: Women and men look for different things
Nothing about a pompous bed frame; what really gives a good bed its quality is the surface on which to lie down, that is, the mattress and the bedside table.
First of all, they must be perfectly complementary so that they are adapted to the particular users.
Numerous factors come into play during the choice, including the owner's weight, height, health status and sex.
The type of interior in which the mattress and the mattress top are placed is also important.
A typical example?
For example, in a weekend cottage that is not usually heated, latex mattresses should not be used because they "heat" more slowly.
They also weigh considerably more than regular polyurethane mattresses.
Therefore, it is necessary to turn them over more often.
If the central channels are not properly ventilated and are above on a firm base, they hold moisture inside.
When choosing a bed, customs also play a role.
Those who have spent a lot of time abroad often use a very high mattress with a soft layer and will have trouble feeling comfortable on a lower, harder surface.
"Almost every hockey player who came back from the NHL complained that they didn't sleep as well here".
"For their bruised shoulders, heels and hips, they needed mattresses with a soft viscoelastic layer".
"This type of mattress is also recommended for people with diabetes who have problems with the nervous system, which makes them misread information from the joints and skin", explains Sylva Hadamcziková, who specializes in upholstered furniture.
Many hockey players, like other customers, have long preferred viscoelastic mattresses.
"Today there is no problem, because they have these proper Tempur and the Italian Magniflex, but also the Czech brand Tropico".
You don't have to be an NHL player to appreciate viscoelasticity anymore.
This "miracle" works in a very simple way.
It optimizes its rigidity and shape based on the heat absorbed or adapts to your body heat.
Nothing puts pressure on it; it won't spin around like a hard game at night.
It just makes you sleep better.
Viscoelasticity also acts as a protection against sores.
When choosing the size of the mattress, add to its height the length of your feet, which is between 21 and 34 centimeters.
A man or woman with a height of about 180 cm will need a bed between 210 and 220 cm.
The minimum width for one person should be, in a double room, 90 cm, for a total of 180 cm.
For single rooms, for example single rooms, a minimum of 120 to 140 cm is recommended.
So a possible visit is also comfortable.
"If not, a simple rule can be applied to calculate the width: when lying on your back, you should have your hands comfortably shrunk to your elbows", advises Helena Prokopová, an engineer and Cechu Čalouníků expert in decorating, who has been working for many years on the subject of healthy sleep and ergonomics of furniture, which she teaches in special schools.
In double rooms, each room needs its own bedside table and mattress, so when buying, you should pay attention to mattress height.
Otherwise, it will be necessary to mount the beds at different heights, which is not always possible in all beds.
Foam mattresses should be at least 14 cm high, models with a spring interior at least 15 cm, of which at least three centimetres are for the coating that adapts to the shapes and softens.
"When touching it with your hand or when settling on the mattress, the springs should certainly not be noticeable", warns Helena Prokopová.
Each mattress requires a specific type of sock.
Fully padded bedrooms, where the mattress and base are like Siamese, have no meaning in the bedroom.
The mattresses breathe badly and you can't wash their covers, which is often done today.
And since we sweat between 0.2 and 0.75 liters of sweat each night, it is clear that after about five or seven years the mattress will begin to remind us of a large (and congested) sieve.
For this reason, specialists reject slogans that talk about a mattress life of up to 25 years or even a lifetime guarantee.
However, everything has a but.
Therefore, the vendors advise: For mattresses that are 120 to 140 centimeters wide, carefully clean and wash the cover, but add a protective mattress that can be removed and washed easily.
Although mattress covers are currently manufactured with zippered closures around their perimeter, so that when they are opened they remain in two parts (something very important for washing and the size of the washing machine!), their handling in larger models (and by a single person) when lifting the mattress can seem like a fight between a flyweight and a heavyweight.
In bed, instead of a bedside table, do you have a hard board?
I never did!
As much as the beds designed to last a night of visitation.
However, it should make (if you do not already have them) ventilation holes in the board and should be used with a mattress with springs inside and a minimum height of 15 cm with springs in bags (like the German Taschenfederkern) and a soft coating.
Polyurethane mattresses should not be used on such bases.
For non-jointed sheet tops containing 14 to 18 sheets, latex or sandwich mattresses (e.g. a combination of latex and coconut fibre) may be used, although a tops with a higher number of sheets, 28 or more, in which the lumbar sheets are reinforced and can be regulated in their stiffness is always preferable.
The articulated sheet sockets should not be used with a spring mattress, as it does not react to reclining.
In addition to adjusting the rigidity of the sheets, shoulder protection can also be used.
This is a special attachment of the sheets that allows the sheets to be pressed or even tilted so that they "circle" the shoulders perfectly during sleep.
For men with very broad shoulders, it's a very important thing.
Even mattress manufacturers remember them, who in the "male" mattresses began to use a softer area just around the shoulders.
They also remember women, for whom they put a softer area around the hips.
For the most demanding customers, there are summits with cross- or table structure with the so-called multitorsion cushioning.
The pressure is distributed between different points and the voltage is lowered.
You should also note that even if you use the right mattress and pillow, if you use a bad pillow (large and "dull"), most of the advantages will disappear.
The basic rule is simple: the pillow should support the head and the corners can only reach the shoulders, so that the muscles of the shoulders can relax.
The recommended size is 50 x 60 cm, which is normal in Scandinavia.
When lying on the side, the pillow should be at the same level (when combined with the shoulder-strengthening cushion or the softer part of the mattress) as the shoulder height.
Modern mattresses seem to have something to do with the original straw-filled mattresses.
Manufacturers are increasingly using natural materials or at least mixtures.
In fact, organic mattresses are in vogue.
The petroleum-based raw materials used to make polyurethane foam are filled with natural oils, such as castor oil or soybean oil.
In fact, virtually all known manufacturers use soy.
"Organic, in the case of mattresses, means that the centre is made of only natural materials", explains Petr Vašíček from Tropico Plus.
Natural substances are also used in the manufacture of the mattress cover, one of the first aloe vera.
But you can also opt for microcapsules, which release a fresh scent of forest or lavender.
There are also differences for men and women.
While men "cool" themselves with vegetable extracts from the breeze, so that the mattress cover absorbs heat and refreshes the body, women prefer to "warm" the cover.
Red pepper extract improves blood circulation, so that women feel warmer.
The favorites at the moment?
The mattresses made of cold foam, which are more porous, with a structure of adapted cells, which makes them more permeable than those of normal polyurethane and offer more permeability.
The combination of different rigidities of cold foam and viscoelasticity allows mattresses to be made from different areas that know perfectly where the head, shoulders and heels go.
A good quality mattress will cost you seven thousand crowns and upwards.
Those with a therapeutic function are usually taxed less, as they are considered to be medical devices.
The first to obtain this advantage in the Czech Republic was Gumotex.
It's hard to save on mattresses and socks.
Sometimes offers from manufacturers or sellers can be accepted, sometimes offering two mattresses for the price of one.
For example, the Magniflex brand offers Duofreeze mattresses with a Memory foam attached to the case for 11,990 crowns.
The second one is free.
The era of viscoelasticity with an open cell structure and high density began with the "cosmic" Tempur material.
It was originally developed for NASA because during takeoffs, astronauts were subjected to enormous overload.
Tempur softens with heat and hardens with cold.
Thus, the human body, when warm, exerts a perfect effect and adapts its pressure optimally.
It is therefore ideal for preventing sores, but also for improving sleep comfort.
Viscoelastic foam is not only used in mattresses, but also for sanitary products, for example for pillows that are placed under the legs and relieve them, as well as their circulation.
Domestic manufacturers, for example, use Eucatherm C or Twinsaver and similar foams.
More and more parents are using tracking devices to monitor their children
Fear of children is leading more and more people to think about tracking them by GPS.
The system, originally designed for vehicle tracking, can also track people's movements and thus contribute, for example, in the case of the disappearance of nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
At the moment the device is about the size of a matchbox, but soon it will be reduced to the size of a watch.
Many people were frightened by the case of the missing Anička and began to be informed about the means available to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of invading their privacy.
"We all try to tell ourselves that this is not spying, but another way to reduce the chances of a tragedy", says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of tracking devices in the Czech market.
"I recognize that in certain cases such devices can be abused, for example if they get into someone's purse without their knowledge, but we have not yet come across such cases".
"Most customers actually buy it for safety reasons", Pilin adds.
He believes that children should always know what the "box" is for and how to use it in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bočková warns that if a child does not want to carry it, he will simply throw it away.
"Even young children are very creative about intentionally missing things if they want to avoid being controlled".
"In the past, parents relied heavily on cell phones, but they could be turned off as easily as the tracking device", says Bočková.
In his view, it is questionable whether such a device is really useful in the event of an attack.
"If it is a premeditated abduction, the perpetrator will almost always check whether the child is wearing some kind of electronic device that can reveal his location".
"Now it's the phone".
"As the use of tracking devices grows, you will also be looking for them, as their sale will undoubtedly be highly advertised".
"In such cases, the criminals are always one step ahead of the police", says the psychologist.
However, he adds that such devices can help in the case of an impromptu attack by a pedophile.
According to Robert Čech of RC Monitoring, which provides tracking services for both vehicles and people, even if the tracking device is destroyed immediately after an attack, their presence can be helpful.
'The device can be configured to regularly send the position after a certain period.'
"If it is damaged, at least it will provide the last position of the person in question".
"The most expensive devices have a built-in tilt meter, so if the person simply slips and remains motionless, the device will immediately issue a warning with the position in question", says Čech.
In its view, such a service can be obtained even with navigation-enabled smartphones, on which only special software must be installed.
The problem with current tracking units is that at the moment they are devices with a size similar to a matchbox or the smaller mobile phones.
So you can get lost.
According to Pilin of Macro Weil, for this reason, tests are currently being conducted with devices that look like a digital clock.
"In addition, they will have the added advantage that a potential aggressor may not identify the device".
"Or that he identifies him after a certain time, which can buy the police time", he adds.
Although tracking devices are worn on the wrist or hung, they will still use the same technology as is used for vehicle tracking.
This is the checking of position with a GPS system (used in normal navigation in the car) combined with the function of a mobile phone that communicates the current position.
The army has enough flares to surround the whole of the Czech Republic, but they only last two years.
The Czech army bought 445 kilometers of fuse to ignite explosives.
Already last year the Ministry of Defense added to its arsenal 224 kilometers of wick.
So they have stocks for 225 years.
The problem is, the lifespan of the fuse is two years, four at most.
The army bought the explosive fuse from STV Group, a.s. for forty million crowns.
The General's staff responded to MF DNES justifying the purchase of such a huge amount of mecha saying that soldiers need for training maneuvers 60 kilometers of mecha a year.
According to the calculations of the army's pyrotechnics, with whom MF DNES contacted, it is decided however that, in such a case, they should carry out such maneuvers with frequent use of explosives every year also all generals, high command officers, and even secretaries and cleaners.
Neither Defense Minister Alexandr Vondr nor Army Captain Vlastimil Picek wanted to be exempt.
Only then could the army be justified in spending 60 kilometres of wick.
That length is equivalent to 25,000 explosions.
Even if it were, the army would have enough supplies for more than ten years.
If, on the contrary, as experts say, for the initial training of each new professional comes with a maximum of two meters of wick, the army would have with the new purchase (even adding the consumption of the units of engineers or special) sufficient stocks for the 225 indicated above.
The soldiers of the rapid intervention brigade complained personally recently to Minister Vondra because they say they barely have ammunition for various weapons, so even the practice of shooting is limited for money.
And let's not talk about the lack of underwear.
"I also cannot understand why we are repeatedly bought such quantities of wick".
"But it's their decision and they will certainly know why they act this way".
"For us, the army is a good customer whom we as a company try to satisfy", admits Jan Děcký, commercial director of STV Group.
Ministry of Defence spokesman Jan Pejšek defends the hundreds of kilometers of mecha by saying he will also have stocks of this "ammunition" for at least ten years.
However, Jan Děcký of STV Group points out that the wick has a lifespan of only four years and, in the case of pyrotechnic products for the army or police, two years.
"If stored in perfect conditions, it can last up to four years", says one soldier, who declined to be named because of possible criticism from the army.
After the end of its service life, each round must be carefully checked to see if it is still reliable and will not harm soldiers.
But these tests are not free and require additional investment.
Another argument from the Ministry is that, when buying 445 kilometers of mecha, he got a discount.
"They cost us 60% less than last year's order of 244 kilometers", says Pejšek, a spokesman for the Ministry of Defense's shopping center.
For comparison's sake, the annual consumption of wick by police pyrotechnics, who dispose of World War II or Soviet army ammunition, has not exceeded 1,500 metres for years.
Also, the police always ask only for just enough ammunition to run out before the end of its useful life.
They decided to do so for safety reasons for pyrotechnicians and, in the meantime, more modern and reliable types of wick can be obtained.
The Ministry is already having clear difficulties in finishing tens of thousands of tonnes of ammunition from the Warsaw Pact era, when the 200,000-strong Czechoslovak army was preparing for a campaign on the Rhine.
According to the pyrotechnicians with whom MF DNES spoke, after a couple of years the following problem will occur with the current one: hundreds of kilometers of old mecha will have to be removed, which is now being bought "cheaply".
I still live off the contacts I made through the contest.
The fact of winning the "Entrepreneur of the Year" contest helped Lukáš Pytloun in selling the franchises of his hotel.
The last edition, the contest "Entrepreneur of the Year" was won by 28-year-old entrepreneur Lukáš Pytloun from Liberec.
His success story looks like something out of a movie.
Lukáš Pytloun loved to travel.
While abroad, he realized that there was a need for quality accommodation at a good price in Liberec.
With the savings he had made from seasonal jobs abroad and a bank loan, he bought a half-ruined five-story house.
Considering he was still in his third year of college, he was really brave.
"At present, the value for money of accommodation in our area has motivated me to do something about it", says Lukáš Pytloun.
He started renting the rebuilt first floor to foreign workers.
All the income he earned he reinvested back into the building, which he gradually converted into a 54-room boarding house.
Since then, in seven years in business, he managed to gradually open in Liberec four guesthouses, two stylish restaurants and two hotels with a total capacity of around 300 in all categories of accommodation.
The most comfortable of all was, until recently, the four-star design hotel Pytloun.
However, this year opened another of the same quality.
"We just signed a contract with a hotel in Ostrov or Tisé, to which we have sold our franchise concept, and other people are showing interest in a Pytloun franchise", said the number one entrepreneur last year.
"This sale of hotel licenses was helped in large part by winning the 'Entrepreneur of the Year' contest", adds Pytloun, grateful.
The victory increased his fame and popularity both in Liberec and the surrounding area.
"People recognized me on the street, they still complimented me often, and I must say, I was very nice", he recalls.
He would certainly recommend that anyone who wants to try out a company that is participating in the competition.
But he feels that it is not necessary to win, but that participation is already beneficial.
He claims that, so far, he continues to live off the contacts and acquaintances that, without the contest, he might not have obtained.
"I have started to collaborate regularly with some people I met through the contest".
The reputation associated with success, in his view, also included in the employees,
About seventy in all.
"I've seen them show greater loyalty and pride in being part of something that got general recognition".
"It is not, by any means, my own personal success, but the result of the hard work of the whole team".
"Only my name is on the front page", says Lukáš Pytloun modestly today.
I wish my successor a calmer year than we had at Farmet .
The euphoria of victory was soon dissipated by the impact of the crisis.
Thanks to the winner's hard work, Farmet may have already been through the worst.
The owner of Farmet, Karel Žďárský, won first prize in the last edition of Vodafone's "Company of the Year" competition last year at the "Slavonic House" in Prague.
The jury appreciated her efforts, with which she managed to turn a small technical workshop in Česká Skalice into a firm with a turnover of hundreds of millions.
"I can say that the award encouraged not only me but all my collaborators and improved our confidence to fight the competition", says last year's winner.
The story of Farmet Company begins with a desire to do something useful.
So when the state offered Karel Žďárský's father the rent of a small workshop as compensation for the seizure of property during communism, he did not hesitate too much; he resigned from his position at the company where she worked and, with a couple of colleagues, founded the company with his father of plastic batteries.
Soon after, they began to specialize in vegetable oil presses.
Eight years later they became the largest automated press manufacturer in central Europe.
They have also gained a greater presence among the non-specialist public after achieving success in the media competition.
"Not only did our customers start to see the Farmet brand as considerably better, but also foreign partners started to value working with a company that was more successful in their country", says Karel Žďárský.
Last year, perhaps, was not only a show of victory euphoria at Farmet.
It was also recognised for its commercial performance up to 2008 and partly in 2009.
And it was precisely 2009 that was the hardest year for machinery sales.
The worsening of the crisis, which had not yet affected so many citizens, caused companies to halt their investment projects and to start to limit the purchase of new machinery or technology.
"We, of course, are not exempt from that situation either".
"Revenue fell by 40%, we had to limit production and even had some layoffs", explains Karel Žďárský.
A viable enterprise must sometimes adopt even unpopular measures.
However, they managed the situation and maintained the company's profits, albeit at lower levels than before the crisis.
Despite everything, where Farmet didn't cut spending was in research and development.
"With the grants we have built a research and training centre, strengthened our presence on the international market and won excellent ratings at national fairs", says Žďárský.
All indications are that they have already put the crisis behind them.
The revenue increases again and with it the number of new employees.
"The new achievement is expected to bring a feeling of victory, but in a calmer atmosphere", says Karel Žďárský.
A survey that exposes ridiculous standards
The Absurdity of the Year poll is part of the business tournament for the fourth time.
He's already managed to eliminate some ridiculous rules.
The unknown winner of the new edition of the year's Absurdity poll was the obligation to bring to the administration documents that officials can access online.
The decision was taken by more than a third of the nearly four thousand voters.
For example, the Social Security Administration requested an extract from the business register, although its officials can obtain it with two mouse movements.
Thanks to the poll, this has changed.
"The Czech social security administration will no longer ask for an extract from the business register when it checks the insured person's taxation", said ČSSZ spokeswoman Jana Buraňová.
The aim of the Absurdity of the Year survey is to find out what rules and regulations businesses and entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic must abide by and to try to eliminate those that are absurd.
This year it is taking part for the fourth time in the business tournament of the Hospodářské noviny publication and is also starting to create a hobby among the general public.
While last year's edition had three thousand voters, this year it has practically reached four thousand.
And this is not surprising, since we still have several legal obligations to be respected simply to trade.
"We are perhaps the world leader in the number of paperwork required for tax returns", says Karel Havlíček of the Association of Small and Medium-sized Enterprises and Entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic.
For years, simplification of business rules has been a stated goal of all governments.
However, in comparison with the rest of the world, the situation is improving especially in the Czech Republic.
According to the World Bank, the Czech Republic is ranked 74th in terms of business conditions, eight places lower than last year.
The Absurdity of the Year contest was first held in 2006 and is repeated every year in the same way.
Anyone can point out some administrative or bureaucratic nonsense every year between April and the end of September, when the contest closes.
Proposals can be made on the website www.firmaroku.cz. The competition organiser then chooses seven candidates for the "pre-prize" and, during October, allows the public to vote on the Internet through www.firmaroku.cz/absurdita and www.ihned.cz.
The absurdity that gets the most votes wins.
For this year's survey, more than 100 were submitted, including 105 rules and regulations that make no sense.
The examples were sent by businessmen, professional associations and journalists.
Among the "finalists" in the competition were, for example, the requirement that vehicles for road and highway maintenance pay tolls or that entrepreneurs with 20 employees, two offices and two bathrooms paint the walls every two years.
The list of this year's seventy proposals is published on the contest pages.
The announcement of the contest, which is always held in early November on Wenceslas Square in Prague, is part of an event in which political and social figures usually participate.
This year, for example, the competition was attended by Eva Svobodová, Director of the Association of Small and Medium-sized Enterprises and Entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic, and Petr Kužel, President of the Chamber of Commerce of the Czech Republic.
"Economic prosperity cannot be maintained if the State continually impedes businessmen, so my aim is to remove every year at least thirty paragraphs that currently unnecessarily complicate trade", announced Minister of Industry and Commerce Martin Kocourek.
Efforts to eliminate absurd regulations are not going to stand idly by.
In 2007, the most annoying thing was the obligation of the entrepreneur to notify the business office of the permanent operation area three days in advance of the intention to go with a position to a fair or exhibition.
This obligation was removed in the new industrial law.
The obligation that finished second in the number of votes in 2007, that is, the notification to the employment office by its foreign workers of business trips of up to 30 days, was eliminated in the so-called green card law.
And the third one goes to the loser.
The Absurdity of 2009 was the regulation for physiotherapists to have in their office a large mirror, a refrigerator and two floor scales.
That is why this year the Ministry of Health issued a communication saying that it had removed the obligation to have a refrigerator.
A new category recognises socially responsible enterprises
Environmental, humanitarian, educational or sporting projects are valued.
The new feature of the fifth edition of the Hospodářské noviny competition is the category "Responsible Enterprise 2010".
The aim of this competition is to support responsible and fair enterprises.
"We want to support companies that are concerned about the impact of their activities on the environment and that support socially responsible activities", says Patrik Bartholdy, regional manager of Vodafone, the mobile operator which organises and sponsors the contest, as in the case of the Rebel of the Year contest.
For this new special subcategory of this year's edition of Vodafone's main competition Enterprise 2010, companies were submitted for which commercial success is not the only long-term goal.
The story of each of them is inspiring and would allow us to write an independent article.
Although the type of activities varies widely from one to another, the common denominator is the support and consideration they offer.
In one case, for example, disabled people, in another personal or health problems of employees.
Among the 14 finalists from across the country was, for example, the Prague software company Et Netera, which supports the formation of informal sports teams among its employees, who then participate in tournaments of various sports.
Another example of a responsible company in the Pardubice area is the company Isolit-Bravo, which has been the main funder for the support of disabled children for seven years.
In Poděbrad, there is a stationery shop which is particularly concerned about the health problems of its workers, who make up over 70% of the workforce.
In Olomouc, the accounting firm MiRyz Soft won, which reduced working hours even below the average of 35 hours a week, without reducing wages.
The certificate was also awarded because it purchases primarily from Czech manufacturers, supports Community activities in the area and respects the environment.
"We try to recycle as much as possible so that our production and management activities have the least possible impact on the environment", explains entrepreneur Miluše Ryznarová.
The IT company Enlogit in Ústí Region also cares about the health of its employees and, with each laptop, has provided them with an ergonomic chair and keyboards; it also supports work from home and uses the catering services of a local protected company at its business events.
"We also support the 'Person en détresse' grant, which specifically helps the local Roma community", says Ondřej Suchý, the company's representative.
The laundry company Praní a čištění in the Karlovy Vary region, whose employees receive special bonuses that affect their pension funds, is also in a good place.
"We provide benefits in food, transport, skills upgrading and leisure", says Josef Strapáč of the winning construction company Bruntál Czasch in the Moravian-Silesian region.
In the category of responsible company of the year, all regional finalists of the Vodafone Enterprise of the Year contest who answered the questions on the registration form and sent it to the organisers before 15 August were automatically nominated.
The organizers removed from the evaluation forms that were incomplete or incorrect.
'If the representatives of the competing companies did not answer the questions, they could not participate in the responsible company of the year competition, but they are not disqualified from the "main" Vodafone company of the year competition.'
"Individual applications for this competition are not allowed, as it is a subcategory of the main competition of Enterprise of the Year", explains Karel Goldman from the consultancy Bison & Rose.
Police made arrests during a public auction at the building of the Agricultural Fund in Pilsen
The anti-corruption police made several arrests in the building of the Agricultural Fund in recent days.
Detectives handcuffed a local media businessman and real estate developer Luboš G.
It appears that the latter is attempting to manipulate an ongoing public auction for the restitution of rights so that the auctioned land would be given to a specific interested party.
I had to pay Luboš G. half a million crowns for it.
"For the moment I can only say that the police are looking for a person for bribery during a public auction and public litigation", said Právo the head of the prosecutor general of Pilsen Antonie Zelená, adding that for the moment can not disclose more details about the ongoing investigation.
After 24 hours, the police released the 46-year-old businessman.
How he could influence the public auction, given the limited official information, can only be speculated.
The spokeswoman of the Agricultural Fund Lubomíra Černá answered Právo's questions by saying that the police actually carried out the arrest at the Pilsen headquarters and it was during a public auction.
"It is a customer, not one of our workers", he said.
According to Černá, the public tender is called 'Call for proposals for land transfer pursuant to the Land Law' and is carried out when several interested parties appear in relation to the land offered.
"These people, during the call, offer a value greater than their restitution, which must be transferred before the value of the land is announced".
"According to the offers, the order of the buyers is determined and then the Agricultural Fund transfers the land to the person who offers the largest offer", explained the Fund's spokeswoman.
Luboš G. had information on who was to be invited to participate in the call and, as he was also an interested person because he had acquired several restitution rights, he proposed to the interested parties in the land that he would not participate in the auction.
Please, he was charging a commission.
That would explain why, at the time of his arrest, he had so much money on him.
Luboš G. had special contacts in the Pilsen Fund for some time.
It was in the case of former PF chief Václav Sankot, who was accused of dispatching the replacement of land for which a construction decision had already been issued.
For example, Luboš G. has just obtained from the Fund land intended for the construction of public infrastructure, in particular on the site where a major road to the Borská pole industrial area is to be built.
Then he exchanged them very profitably with the magistrate for a house in the very historic center of the city with a much higher value.
In this case, the city council had to intervene because otherwise the blocked land would prevent the construction.
Families will have to pay an additional cost of several hundred crowns a month
Households will have to pay from January not only for all types of energy, but also for water and electricity, heating supplements and, in some cases, higher rents.
The Commission has already made a number of proposals to this effect.
The price of electricity rises by 4.6%, gas by around 2%, in some cities they will have to pay up to 10% more for water supply and many also increase the price of central heating.
The electricity price increase for families living in apartments should amount to about 100 crowns more per year than now.
However, the main electricity suppliers reduced prices, as support for the production of energy from renewable sources, in particular PV, has increased.
However, gas is becoming moderately expensive, especially when heating is used more and therefore consumption is higher.
In this case, you should also have a couple of hundred crowns more a year.
While electricity and gas are becoming more expensive throughout the country, the price change for central heating varies from place to place.
The price hike is mainly planned by the largest municipality.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Králové will pay an additional 50 CZK per month for central heating from January onwards, while families in Liberec will pay an additional CZK 1,000 per year.
Residents in Prague will also have to bear a 9% increase in the price of water and heating, especially if the city increases infrastructure rents.
If the rent does not change, the Prague residents will pay an additional 6.8%.
Prices in Prague, however, will remain among the lowest in the whole country.
In northern Bohemia, where current prices are among the highest, both rates will rise by 7.4%.
They may significantly increase rental prices for 450,000 apartments rented in Prague, where the regulation will end in January.
For example, CPI Byty, which owns about 2,500 flats in Ústí nad Labem, will increase rents by up to 100% from January.
The company will take to court anyone who disagrees with the new lease.
Regulated rents, which benefit residents of about 300,000 flats, could rise next year by up to 10%.
The young Czechs get drunk on Fernet and rum.
Fernet, rum, vodka and even good whiskeys stolen from his parents.
These are the drinks that cause young drinkers under the age of fifteen to end up in medical care.
Children who end up lying in the hospital continuously to get over a hangover are no longer an exception.
This is derived from the experience of doctors who encounter such cases at hospital pediatric admissions.
"Drinking beer or wine is no longer fashionable, because it takes too long to get drunk".
"Now the trend is strong alcoholic drinks", Luděk Pelikán, chief of pediatrics at the Hořovice Hospital in central Bohemia, tells Právo.
"When they manage to grab a bottle from their father from the cupboard, it may be whiskey, but it's usually Fernet and vodka".
"The advantage of vodka is that it is lightened with juice and has a less pungent odor", he explains.
This is also confirmed by the spokeswoman of the Motol University Hospital, Eva Jurinová.
"Usually, it's Fernet or rum".
"Those are the modern alcoholic drinks, particularly among schoolchildren".
"In some cases, they use spirits they picked up at home", Jurinová adds.
According to Chief Pelican, it's 13- and 14-year-old drinkers who usually show up at hospitals.
Before moving to Hořovice, where she has been working since this year, she worked for a decade in pediatrics in Motol, where ambulances took young people from nearby areas.
"A girl had to come in maybe four times".
"It started at age 12, when she was brought in with 3.5 alcohols in her blood, plus a blend of ecstasy", says the department doctor on this case.
"He was at the Holešovice fair at some dance party".
"The interesting thing is that her mother was not surprised that her daughter disappeared for 48 hours", the boss is surprised.
It is precisely the lack of interest or even clear tolerance of parents toward their children's drinking that is considered the main cause of the increase in alcohol consumption among young people.
Experts point out that in the case of children, there is no such thing as dependency.
"An alcoholic is defined as a person who has been chronically dependent on alcohol for several years, with all the associated phenomena, which do not occur in children".
"In those who drink alcohol repeatedly, it is more likely due to a systematically failed social or family environment", explains Chief Pelikán.
According to the spokeswoman Jurinová, this year in the pediatric clinic of Motol were hospitalized until mid-November forty drunk children.
However, statistics only show those who come with severe poisoning and must stay in hospital.
Young drinkers who, after a roadside medical examination, go home to their parents or the police, don't count.
In addition to the cases where children simply gather after school and drink spirits, for Pelikán there are three seasonal ups and downs worth mentioning: Witches' Day, New Year's Eve and the end of the school year.
"In such a situation, they drink to the bad grades or, on the contrary, celebrate the beginning of the holidays".
"On Halloween, I have seen up to seven drunk children admitted at once", adds Pelikán.
Drinkers who spend the night in rehab under the supervision of doctors paradoxically have the advantage of not having a terrible hangover at home the next day.
Morning headaches, caused by dehydration and lack of glucose, are prevented by injecting a serum with glucose and nutrients that the body lacks.
"They're better off, because after a hectic night, they get up and feel no pain".
"They're just confused about where they are", Pelikán notes, adding that patients often lose their good humor at least when they see the expenses they've generated.
The cost of an ambulance transfer and hospitalization in a critical care unit can run into tens of thousands of crowns.
"I have often used the cost as a means of educating them, when on the visit I tell the children directly how much their drunkenness has cost them and that they would have to spend the whole summer in a youth work if you were to earn enough to be paid that night", adds Pelikán.
The health insurance, in his view perhaps as a regressive measure, which usually reimburses people for treatment costs, does not do so in the case of children who drink.
Two L-159s are in the hands of foreigners in Spain for the first time
Two L-159 aircraft out of a total of five, which the Czech Ministry of Defence replaced with the Casa C-295M aircraft, departed on Tuesday for Seville, where the Casa aircraft manufacturer - EADS is based.
It is the first time that a device of this type has been in the hands of someone other than the Czech army.
At the moment, they were only abroad for practice or demonstration flights.
It is the two-seater version L-159T1, which was used by the Czech army until then and was still in flight condition.
The remaining three aircraft are the single-seat L-159s.
These are still being held at Aer Vodochody and the intermediary of the sale, the company Omnipol, already took over them last week.
Jan Peješk, from the defense press department, indicates that it is not yet known when the planes will be physically withdrawn from Vodochody.
"The L-159 single-seaters, on the other hand, were separated from the repaired aircraft for some time, without additional investments or contributions from the Ministry".
"The two-seater L-159T1s were exchanged in their current state", he told Právo Pejšek.
He added that the army is not without two-seat aircraft, since in May 2009 the army signed a contract with Aer Vodochody for an amount of 200 million kroner for the construction of four unnecessary two-seat L-159 devices.
One of the new planes was delivered to the army in July, the other will be delivered by the end of the year.
According to Pejšek, EADS has committed to adding the aircraft to the equipment of some Allied countries.
"The contract clearly states that EADS is the company that will retire the L-159 aircraft and that they will be used for pilot training by NATO countries".
"It is therefore up to the buyer to decide how they will use them in this context", says Pejšek.
The newspaper Hospodářské noviny published early that, for example, the Spanish army is not interested in the L-159s.
The exchange of five L-159s for a Casa aircraft and the purchase of three more aircraft for 3.500 billion crowns were approved last year by the government of Mirek Topolánek.
The Ministry of Defence did not call a tender for the purchase and negotiated directly with EADS.
The current defense directorate claims that the exchange promotes the future export of L-159s abroad.
The Czech army bought 72 aircraft from Aer and only uses 24, so they want to sell the rest.
The purchase of Casa planes may have legal consequences.
The European Commission has already sued the Czech Ministry of Defence before the European Court of Justice for choosing the aircraft by a European tender rather than by contacting a single manufacturer.
The army has already received three Casa planes and the last one should arrive at Prague's Kbely airport in fourteen days.
A longer index finger than the ring finger indicates a lower risk of cancer
Men with a longer index finger than the ring finger are subject to a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the startling conclusion of a study published Wednesday in the British Journal of Cancer.
It could be dependent on the level of testosterone, the male hormone.
"Our results indicate that relative finger length may be a simple test of prostate cancer risk, particularly for men up to 60 years of age", said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
Therefore, the finger could help determine which men should be screened for prostate cancer, particularly if this trait is associated with genetic risk or other harmful factors, such as family health problems, Eeles says.
During the period 1994-2009, he followed up with a British counterpart on more than 1,500 prostate cancer patients and, simultaneously, 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had a right index finger shorter than the ring finger.
They were as likely to develop prostate cancer as 19 percent of those with fingers the same length.
For men with an index finger longer than the ring finger, this risk was reduced by 33%; for men under 60 years of age, the reduction was 87%.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers in question, as determined in the prenatal period, reflects different levels of hormones to which the fetus is exposed in the womb.
A lower testosterone level corresponds to a longer index.
Previous studies have shown that testosterone influences the development of prostate cancer.
The great Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, Professor Václav Pačes, told ČTK that he is aware of the study, but that he does not think that the link between finger length and cancer can be "fully demonstrated".
Czech Republic in snow: D1 and D5 closed
The Czech Republic, like most of Europe, was covered in snow on Thursday.
Roads and sidewalks are mostly covered in compact snow and snow machines have been running all night in many areas.
In the morning the D5 road between kilometres 89 and 93 in the direction of Rozvadov was closed due to various industrial and passenger vehicle accidents, as was the D1 in Brno in the direction of Prague.
The news was broadcast by the operator of Ústředního automotoklubu (ÚAMK).
In the 91st kilometer a truck broke down, in the 93rd two industrial vehicles collided causing injuries.
Several cars also ended up in the ditch.
There are also problems on the D1 motorway at kilometer 185 towards Prague.
Two trucks collided there.
Drivers should either drive slowly after Brno at kilometer 190 or cross Brno and join at kilometer 182 at Kývalce.
Traffic jams have formed there for several kilometers.
There was also an accident on the D11 road, just outside Prague.
Prague is covered in a layer of snow several centimeters high and the thermometers are at -7 degrees Celsius.
Traffic is becoming congested in Prosek, for example, although Štěrboholská is also congested.
The safest means of transportation is the subway.
Trams run late, for example on the line between Karlovo náměstí and Náměstí Míru.
At eight o'clock in the morning, another state of crisis will occur in Prague.
The problems also affect the railways and the airport.
Because of the snow, the Czech railway company had to cancel seven connections for three fast.
The problems concern, for example, the line between Prague and Kralupy or Prague and Beroun.
Travelers should check the current situation.
Ruzyně Airport was closed from 11pm on Wednesday until 5am.
Today, most roads in southern Moravia are free to drive, but with extreme caution.
Three secondary roads are closed to traffic in Vyškovska, snow is forming in Brněnska and chains are needed in Blanenska to access certain access roads to the highest points.
One of the worst affected places was Vyškovsko.
The following routes are currently closed: Rousínov - Slavkov, Bohdalice - Kučerov and also Šaratice - Milešovice.
To clear them, milling machines will be required.
At the moment, we cannot say when they will be opened to traffic.
In Hodonínska, caution is required in the area of the Bílé Karpaty (White Carpathians).
Roads in the region, which, as a protected natural area, should simply be left inert, are piling up up up to five centimetres of snow, ČTK reports.
In the Czech Republic, between two and ten centimeters of snow fell, while more fell in northern Bohemia, where the snow cover reached 18 centimeters.
In the Moravian-Silesian region, about six inches of snow fell.
Snowfall is gradually receding in the Czech Republic.
American soldiers have a new "smart weapon"
The American military is deploying in Afghanistan a new "smart" weapon, known at the moment only by the code name XM-25.
The generals hope the new rifle will influence the local conflict with the Taliban and "change the game progress" to their victory.
The new weapons are like a small pistol with extremely precise aim.
His bullets are laser-fired with a range of several meters.
The special 25 mm caliber ammunition created for this rifle and the high explosive load it contains make it actually function as a small grenade.
The projectiles can be programmed to explode not only when they hit the target, but at any point in their ballistic path.
