Support for democracy in Latin America continues to increase, as does support for private enterprise.
Crime is more of a concern than unemployment.
Moreover, in much of the region, Brazil is seen as a more influential country than the United States.
These are some of the findings of the latest Latinobarometer survey conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
Since the survey has been carried out regularly since 1995, it allows the monitoring of changes in attitudes in the region.
The results of this year's survey, conducted in September and early October, highlight two related issues.
The first is the relatively lively humor that prevails in Latin America.
The second is the increasing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased considerably in several countries on the Pacific coast of South America (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% a year since 2002, support for democracy has risen from a low of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also grew in Mexico, where the economy has recovered after a sharp decline in production last year.
However, only half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries in the region, are convinced democrats, which is lower than the regional average (see Chart 2).
Some 44% of respondents in the region were satisfied with the way democracy operates in practice in their country, the same as last year but considerably higher than the 25% recorded in 2001 (Graph 3).
Some 34% said they trusted their country's Congress and 45% their government, the same number as last year in both cases, but considerably higher than in 2003 (17% and 24%, respectively).
A decade ago, economic turmoil in Latin America severely affected support for democracy.
The fact that it has persisted during the global financial crisis is probably because many Latin American countries were only affected by a brief recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, a stronger social safety net has helped to protect the poorest.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty only increased marginally in 2009 and has fallen again this year, to 32 percent.)
However, mood varies considerably from country to country (see Chart 4).
Brazil's good economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, is reflected in a general sense of progress.
Such feelings are less common in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more severe and violent crime has increased.
For the second time since the surveys began, more respondents in Latin America cite crime, rather than unemployment, as the most serious problem facing their country (see Chart 5).
About 31 percent say that they or a close relative has been a victim of crime in the past year, a drop from 38 percent last year and the lowest percentage recorded since 1995.
The most positive economic performance is reflected in increased support for private enterprise and the market economy: around 71% of respondents in the region say that private enterprise is indispensable for development, compared with only 56% in 2007 (see Chart 6).
Some 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that will allow their country to develop, up from 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela feel the same way (and 80% support private companies), even though their leftist president, Hugo Chávez, is expropriating numerous private companies.
Brazil is the country that exercises the greatest leadership in the region, as indicated by 19% of respondents (vs. 18% last year), followed by the United States (vs. 9% last year) and Venezuela (vs. 9% a year ago).
However, the United States is the country considered most influential by respondents in Mexico and much of Central America, while Venezuela holds that title in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
