Mr. Kirchner, who took power in 2003 when Argentina was on the brink of economic collapse, made growth and poverty reduction his priorities, rather than controlling inflation.
He refused to negotiate with the IMF, pressured the private sector and had the INDEC, the statistical institute, adapt official inflation statistics.
Will President Fernández now moderate these policies?
He's called for meetings between the private sector and union leaders.
In addition, officials say they want to limit wage increases next year to 18%.
The economy has been boosted by high prices of Argentine agricultural exports to the world.
However, inflation has limited the growth momentum achieved with a large devaluation in 2002.
Perhaps that is why Mrs Fernandez is giving signs of wanting to restore Argentina's financial links with the rest of the world.
At the beginning of the year, the government reached an agreement with bondholders who had refused a prior forced restructuring of the debt that Argentina had not repaid in 2001.
It seems that Mrs Fernandez is now about to conclude an agreement with the creditors of the governments of the Paris Club, to which she owes some 6.7 billion dollars.
The Kirchners always insisted that this would not involve IMF supervision, as is usually the case.
However, last month Amado Boudou, the Minister of Economy, announced that the Fund will offer "technical assistance" to develop a new index of national consumption prices, which seems to be the prelude to the cleanup of the INDEC.
It is unclear whether President Fernández wants to continue in politics when her term ends, given that she no longer has her husband by her side.
If he does, he will need to win the support of the middle class, much of whom have grown tired of Kirchnerism.
When Argentines return from their summer vacation in March, the wave of sympathy for her will have faded.
If she wants to win another election, she'll have to decide whether or not to quietly repudiate many of her husband's policies.
Half a cheer for China
Taiwanese voters are slowly approaching a kind of closer union with the mainland.
What does Taiwan think of its big brother across the strait?
More than 7.5 million voters, 70% of eligible voters, turned out on November 27 to elect mayors and councillors from five urban districts in what seems to be a broad assessment of President Ma Ying-jeou.
Mr. Ma himself has become a champion of sentiments for the continent, forging innovative business ties, including a partial free trade agreement, the biggest change in relations with China since 1949.
Mr. Ma passed the test, but by a short shot.
Although his Kuomintang (KMT) party ended up winning three of the five mayoral elections, it failed to secure a majority of the vote.
Instead, the Democratic Progressive Party (DPP), which has leaned towards full independence from Taiwan, won almost 50% of all votes against 45% for the KMT.
If it had been the presidential election, Mr. Ma would be in trouble.
Since his election two years ago, his party's share of the vote has fallen by about 8%.
For the first time, the PPD tied the KMT in the town halls.
The election featured typical Taiwanese election elements, including noisy campaign trucks and large crowds with flags and lightly dressed girls dancing.
Nor was the mysterious rigorous assassination attempt.
Sean Lien, the son of Lien Chan, honorary chairman of the KMT, was campaigning for one of the KMT candidates the night before the election.
A man in the crowd shot the young man directly in the face, wounding and killing a passerby.
The funny thing is, it's not clear if the man intended to hurt Lien or get back at the candidate.
In any case, says Tsai Ing-wen, the leader of the PPD, the shooting affected the election, sowing suspicion about the PPD and causing voters to lean towards the KMT.
Perhaps the only big winner of the campaign was China.
It was surprising that the continent itself was not involved.
Instead, the candidates talked about plans for public housing and job creation.
Taiwan normally enjoys its de facto independence and detests China's military threat.
As a result, the KMT usually avoids publicizing its ties to the government in Beijing.
But this time too the PPD avoided encouraging anti-China sentiment.
It responds to the new awareness that Chinese trade is essential to Taiwan's economic survival.
Mr Ma said that his policy towards China was confirmed to be acceptable to most Taiwanese.
The government of Beijing is expected to continue to bribe them with trade, in line with its strategy to bring Taiwan back into the fold.
China wasted no time in sending a negotiator to Taipei to prepare a summit on investment protection and medical cooperation.
I am sure that you would like to see political integration as well, but first things first.
The best thing to do is wait until after the 2012 presidential election.
In any case, the PPD has reinvented itself.
Two years ago, it was in a bad situation: its former leader, Chen Shui-bian, was jailed on corruption charges.
President from 2000 to 2008, he openly advocated explicit independence.
However, under Ms Tsai's leadership, a new generation of moderates has emerged and the PPD is striving to attract professionals and young people.
Ms. Tsai has been welcomed as the DPP's presidential candidate, as has Su Tseng-chang, who served under Chen.
Now his party is doing everything it can to prove that it can also have relations with Beijing.
Mrs Tsai announced plans to set up an expert group to act as a point of contact between the DPP and China, provided that negotiations can be carried out without preconditions.
Ms Tsai tells the Taiwanese public that her party represents a "reliable alternative" to Mr Ma's hasty approach to China.
Mr. Chen seems furious about the change.
In a statement issued from his cell, he claimed that the DPP candidates would have fared better if they had insisted that Taiwan is an independent country.
He even ordered Mr. Su, a pragmatist, not to run for president.
Even without Mr. Chen's intervention, the PPD will have a hard time choosing between its potential candidates.
The KMT must also make an examination of conscience.
Mr. Ma's ratings have been poor, despite impressive economic growth; KMT candidates have not wanted to campaign with him.
Its lack of popularity seems to be primarily due to unemployment and the growing gap between rich and poor.
A KMT spokesman claims that he will restructure his cabinet as well as local teams.
The large samples of the DPP suggest that Taiwan's support for a rapprochement is limited.
At the same time, most Taiwanese consider economic integration with China inevitable.
According to Antonio Chiang, a well-known columnist, "the point of no return has already been crossed".
Grammy nominations: Jazz singer Esperanza Spalding is the surprise choice in the category of Breakthrough Artist.
Act on a president's request and people will probably notice you.
Esperanza Spalding, the 26-year-old bassist and jazz singer personally selected by President Obama to perform at his Nobel Peace Prize ceremony in 2009, was one of the Grammys surprises this year with a high-profile nomination in the Best New Artist category.
Considering that Spalding has been an acclaimed jazz figure since his 2008 album, "Esperanza", the nomination is thought-provoking, but respects Grammy rules that require an artist to have released no more than three albums before recording the one that "determines the public identity of that artist".
Her ambitious 2010 album, "Chamber Music Society", was certainly a breakthrough and, given her light and pleasant vocal style as well as a great skill with pop, funk and Latin rhythm influences, one can at least draw a distinction between Spalding and the road to success of Norah Jones in 2003, the closest equivalent to the Grammy voters, who have lately concentrated on the jazz realm for this category.
In the other categories, Grammy voters rightly honored Vijay Iyer Trio's "Historicity", an exciting and magnificent record that was a favorite last year.
Among Iyer's competitors are veteran saxophonist James Moody on "Moody 4B" and keyboardist John Beasley on "Positootly".
Trombone Shorty, a favorite New Orleans stringer and regular guest on HBO's "Treme", was honored in the contemporary jazz category, which otherwise leans considerably toward fusion as in the albums of Stanley Clarke, John McLaughlin and Jeff Lorber.
Darcy James's wild punk Argue's Secret Society gained well-deserved recognition in the big band category, competing against the great chamber jazz of the Billy Childs Ensemble and the ever-risky Dave Holland, whose live album with his octet, "Pathways", was a great example of the bassist's democratic leadership in his band.
Grammy nominations: Michael Daugherty and Steve Mackey for best direction of classical albums
The classical music nominations for the 53rd Grammy Awards include a mix of musicians and composers from around the world.
The main nominations were for Michael Daugherty for "Deus Ex Machina", for piano and orchestra, in five movements, and Steve Mackey for "Dreamhouse", an eclectic three-movement orchestral work.
Among the nominees with ties to Southern California are Estonian composer Arvo Pärt for his Symphony No. 4, "Los Angeles", a piece commissioned by the Los Angeles Philharmonic and premiered at the Walt Disney Concert Hall in 2009.
Los Angeles-based composer Avner Dorman is also nominated for his Mandolin Concerto.
The classical music nominations are distributed in thirteen categories that include orchestral, opera, choral and solo albums.
The classical producer of the year category includes five nominees: Blanton Alspaugh, David Frost, Tim Handley, Marina and Victor Ledin, and James Mallinson.
The nominees for the classical music album are Bruckner for Symphonies No. 3 and No. 4 by the Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra; Daugherty for "Deus Ex Machina" and "Metropolis Symphony" by the Nashville Symphony Orchestra; Steven Mackey for "Dreamhouse" by the Boston Modern Orchestra Project and Synergy Vocals; "Sacrificium - the Art of the Castrati" by various artists; and Verdi's "Requiem" by the Chicago Symphony Orchestra and Chorus.
In the opera category, the nominees are Berg for "Lulu" by the orchestra of the Royal Opera House; Adolf Hasse for "Marc Antonio and Cleopatra" by Ars Lyrica Houston; Kaija Saariaho for "L'Amour de Loin" by the Deutsches Symphonie-Orchester Berlin; Rodion Shchedrin for "The Enchanted Wanderer" by the orchestra and choir of the Mariinsky Theatre; and Arthur Sullivan for "Ivanhoe" by the BBC National Orchestra of Wales.
Composers nominated for a Grammy for contemporary compositions include Pärt for Symphony No. 4, Daugherty for "Deus Ex Machina", Hans Werner Henze for "Appassionately Plus", Magnus Lindberg for "Graffiti" and Shchedrin for "The Enchanted Wanderer".
Pärt's Symphony No. 4 premiered at Disney Hall in January 2009 in a session recorded by the Los Angeles Philharmonic, conducted by Esa-Pekka Salonen.
The piece, approximately 30 minutes long, is nicknamed "Los Angeles" and is dedicated to former oil tycoon Mikhail Khodorkovsky, imprisoned in Russia.
Dorman's "Mandolin Concerto" is nominated for instrumental solo performance with orchestra.
The Los Angeles composer wrote the 15-minute piece specifically for mandolin player Avi Avital, who performed the concert with the New York-based Metropolis Ensemble.
"He composed it with sounds from the Middle East and numerous scales and rhythms from North Africa", Dorman stated in a telephone interview.
Conductor Pierre Boulez, 85, was nominated in the category of orchestral function, for conducting the Chicago Symphony Orchestra during a recording of Stravinsky's works.
Among the instrumental soloists nominated are pianists Nelson Freire and Marc-André Hamelin; organist Paul Jacobs; violinist Julia Fischer; and harpist Sarah Schuster Ericsson.
The nominees for vocal soloists are all women this year: Anne Sofie Von Otter, Cecilia Bartoli, Lucia Duchonová, Vivica Genaux and Measha Brueggergosman.
In the classical mixing category, soprano Jessye Norman was nominated for her recording of "Roots - My Life, My Song".
Proposed mosque in Temecula gets approval from the planning commission
The mosque project for Temecula has won unanimous support from the local planning commission after more than five hours of often heated public testimony.
Critics attacked the project saying it encourages terrorism and traffic jams.
However, the committee members decided Wednesday night that the new religious center would be aesthetically impressive and comply with local law.
"Many good people came to show their support, whether Christians or Jews or Baha'is, of all religions", Hadi Nael, president of the Islamic Center of the Temecula Valley, said Thursday morning.
"The truth is, as an American citizen, I'm proud of you".
"It shows that justice prevails".
"The opposition is really minimal", he adds.
"Only they talk too loud".
"There are wonderful people in this valley".
The meeting began at 6 p.m. and lasted virtually until midnight; most of the time was spent with people speaking out for or against the center, roughly the same number on each side, according to the Press-Enterprise.
The debate continued on the newspaper's website.
"America no longer exists", one of the comments read.
"It's another Planet of the Apes with Mrs. Liberty dead in the sand".
"America has fallen".
The plans to build Islamic centers have also sparked protests in other parts of the country, including near ground zero, the area of New York where the September 11, 2011 attacks took place.
In the Temecula Valley, Imam Mahmoud Harmoush has denounced acts of violence.
His congregation of about 135 families has been living smoothly in Riverside County for years, but they wanted a larger, better space than the warehouse they rented on a property they shared with a manufacturer of water filtration systems.
