An arsenic-resistant microbe raises the possibility of new life forms on Earth or elsewhere.
The discovery of a strange bacterium that can use arsenic as one of its nutrients expands the possibility of finding new life forms on Earth and possibly on other planets.
Although the researchers discovered the curious bacteria here on Earth, they say it proves that it's possible for life forms to exist without the main elements they considered essential.
"This organism has a double capacity".
"It can grow on either phosphorus or arsenic".
"That makes it very peculiar, but it is close to being a truly 'alien' type of life", said Paul C. W. Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of the report appearing in Thursday's online edition of Science.
For a long time, six major elements were considered essential for life - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus, and sulfur.
However, researchers have found that the bacteria found in Mono Lake, California, can continue to grow after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
"It makes you wonder what else is possible", said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
According to Anbar, the finding is important for the search for life on planets other than Earth, since researchers need to be able to recognize life, to know what it looks like.
The study focuses on a microbe discovered on Earth.
However, the call for a press conference to discuss the discovery, in which no details of the discovery were disclosed, generated a lot of speculation on the Internet about the possibility that the report indicated the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
He didn't.
What the discovery "does show is that in other planetary environments, there may be organisms that use other elements to drive their biochemistry and that the set of 'standard' elements we think are indispensable for life may not be as fixed", said Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, Milton Keynes, UK.
Cockell wasn't part of the research team.
"This work is novel because it demonstrates the substitution of one element for another in biochemistry and basic biochemical structure", Cockell added.
The discovery was not made by chance.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Astrobiology Institute, who led the study, focused on Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, so he speculated that a microbe exposed to both could substitute one for the other.
"Arsenic is toxic primarily because its chemical behavior is similar to that of phosphorus".
"As a result, it may be difficult for organisms to differentiate them".
"However, arsenic is different enough that it doesn't work as well as phosphorus, so it comes in and, so to speak, it cripples the biochemical machinery", Anbar explains.
The researchers collected the bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed them to increasing concentrations of arsenic, which they managed to adapt to and use to grow.
The microbe grows best with phosphorus, but the fact that it can be shown to live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that there may be a life form that uses arsenic naturally, either in other areas of the Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said that the idea of replacing arsenic with phosphorus is not new, but no example of it ever being found.
Arsenic was more common in the earliest ages of the Earth, he noted, so researchers speculated that early life forms may have used it.
"It does suggest that there could be other means of generating life, not just the way life formed on Earth in the old days", said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy, and the National Institutes of Health.
The stolen dogs that were missing in Compton have been found.
The two missing dogs from the four stolen dogs have been found outside the Bellflower Motel, Los Angeles County Sheriff's officials said Thursday.
The four competition dogs, two Akitas and two Pembroke Welsh Corgi, went missing Tuesday when someone stole the 2006 Chevrolet Express pickup truck they were spending the night in in front of Bellflower Motel 6, authorities said.
Two of the canines were recovered Wednesday afternoon and the remaining two were found late Wednesday night, according to Steve Whitmore, a spokesman for the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department.
"The good news is that the dogs are fine", Whitmore said.
"They are in good condition".
"They've returned to their rightful owners".
Whitmore would not specify exactly where the dogs were found, in what neighborhood, or the circumstances of the discovery.
"An investigation is underway".
"We don't want to say anything", Whitmore said.
"We're following up on some leads".
The dog owners, Kristina Rickard and David Peek, could not be found for comment Thursday.
They met their two Akitas at a county animal shelter in Downey on Wednesday afternoon.
Deputy found the van and the two dogs separately in Compton.
