The other dogs were to be exhibited in other competitions scheduled for the days leading up to the AKC/Eukanuba championship, Peek told The Times on Wednesday.
Southern California is one of the stops on the couple's nearly two-month dog-racing tour.
Monday night, Peek and Rickard checked into the motel.
They usually stay in motels and park their van right outside their bedroom window.
They were carrying three other dogs (a boxer puppy, a Parson Russell terrier and a Brittany, who slept with them in the motel room).
But they left the Akitas and Corgis in the van because they have a thick coat and they'd be cooler.
They left the windows slightly open so that the dogs could breathe fresh air.
Peek and Rickard reported the van stolen Tuesday morning at 6:00 a.m.
Peek had said they would offer a reward to anyone who could lead them to the Corgis, equipped with microchips to identify them.
Thursday it wasn't clear if a reward would be given or not.
The lion is ready to roar again as MGM's restructuring gets final court approval
After 18 months of confusion and uncertainty, MGM has finally gotten the green light to start over.
On Thursday, a federal bankruptcy judge in New York officially approved the plan "pre-armed" by creditors to write off about $5 billion in debt, paving the way for the 86-year-old entertainment company to focus its efforts on producing and releasing movies and TV shows.
Thursday's ruling confirms that the plan meets the requirements of the U.S. bankruptcy code, so there are no other legal obstacles to MGM relaunching under Spyglass Entertainment founders Gary Barber and Roger Birnbaum, who will become the chief executives of what will be a small studio.
The staff will be reduced from 400 to approximately 320 members.
In fact, MGM will not exit Chapter 11 until JPMorgan Chase closes a planned $500 million loan facility to finance the operations and production of the new MGM.
The investment bank is currently syndicating the credit, which on its own is contributing $75 million, and is expected to be funded by mid-December.
The restructuring process of the studio began in May 2009, when the investment bank Moelis and Co. was hired to provide management advice necessary to order its finances, while it struggled to make interest payments of $300 million a year.
In August, Director Harry Sloan was replaced by Stephen Cooper, a former Enron Chairman and bankruptcy recovery expert known for his work at Krispy Kreme Doughnuts.
Moelis and Cooper's attempts to resolve MGM's financial troubles and satisfy the studio's more than 140 creditors, took much longer than expected.
After several months of discussions, at the end of 2009 the parties agreed to put the company up for sale.
However, the auction attracted few bidders and none willing to pay the more than $2 billion that the creditors were seeking.
Before the spring of this year, he returned to the design table as the MGM team began work on a restructuring plan that, after months of internal debate and disagreement, was finally backed by creditors in late October.
When MGM officially emerges from bankruptcy in the next few weeks, Moelis and Cooper's companies will receive multi-billion dollar bonuses for their work.
Moelis and Co., which has already received $1.2 million, will get a payment of $9.5 million.
Cooper's companies, which have been raising $375,000 a month for their company management services, will receive a $4 million "success fee".
Barber and Birnbaum plan to resume production at MGM, which released only one film this year and has assembled an annual slate of seven or eight films to be released in 2012.
They also plan to co-finance two films based on "The Hobbit", along with Warner Bros.
The studio needs to take out a separate loan of between $265 million and $275 million to finance its share of those two films, which will be directed by Peter Jackson.
Investor Carl Icahn, who owns approximately 18% of MGM's debt, had been trying to arrange a merger of the studio with Lions Gate Entertainment, in which he is the largest shareholder.
However, recent talks between the two companies did not result in an agreement.
Tech Toys wants to keep its gift budget in balance.
While the iPad is the leading contender to be the most wonderful toy of this year, followed, perhaps, by the Microsoft Kinect video game system, both can mean a significant dent in your gift budget.
Consider that for the price of an iPad you can buy five BMX bikes for $99 each, and a Kinect game costs the same as 10 classic jump ropes adorned with beads, or about 48 cans of Play-Doh.
But there are ways to keep your gift budget in balance.
I recently visited three national toy retailers, Wal-Mart, Toys "R" Us and BJ's Wholesale Club, to see what electronic toys I could buy for under $80.
It was immediately clear that Moore's Law had been working; this year's tech toy will probably have more power, cost the same and even a little less compared to last year's.
Also, while there are generally fewer new toys with associated websites, two of the more well-known of this type, Webkinz and Club Penguin, have more offerings.
And button-battery-powered toys are on the rise, as are rechargeable battery toys.
Here are some recommendations.
(All prices are from Toys "R" Us, unless otherwise stated.)
Sing-a-ma-jigs (Mattel, $13 for ages 3 and up) are stuffed toys the size of a guinea pig that sing a note when their bellies are squeezed.
One squeeze equals a note, and a second squeeze starts to put together a song.
If you buy more than one, they'll sing in harmony.
Caution: Once you start squeezing, you can't stop.
For singing combined with dancing, Dance Star Mickey (Fisher-Price, $60, for 2 years and older) is the best choice.
Borrowing from last year's Elmo Live technology, the 14-inch animatronic doll plays turn-shifting games like Simon Says, and can do the moonwalk, thanks to its innovative articulated feet with locking wheels.
The children who tried the toy used Mickey as a dance instructor, although their parents complained about the lack of volume control.
If you're a kid in the '80s, you may remember Alphie, one of the first computerized educational toys.
He's back (Hasbro/Playskool, $40, for 3 years and up), with a backpack full of question cards designed to turn a car ride into a session with a self-correcting exercise book occurring.
If you are reluctant to give your child your smartphone, here are three independent alternatives.
VTech's MobiGo ($60, 3-8 years) is the cheapest and easiest to use, featuring a qwerty keyboard; although games do not teach as effectively as the Leapster Explorer ($70, 3-12 years), it is the first major tweak of the Leapster line, with a newer and brighter screen.
None of the versions are compatible with the old cartridges.
Fisher-Price's iXL ($90, 3-7 years) uses an iTunes-like system to present games and e-books, and has an SD card slot that allows viewing family photos.
Finally, Scrabble Flash ($30, Hasbro, for ages 8 and up) is a game of five blocks barely larger than a matchbox, each with its own LED screen.
The goal is to put words together by placing the blocks in a row before time runs out; it's formidable for an impromptu word-building competition.
More and more toys have some kind of online connection.
Based on their presence in toy stores alone, the two largest are Webkinz and Club Penguin.
To buy your child a pet online at Club Penguin, for example, you can get a Disney Club Penguin 2 Mix 'N Match Figure Pack, ($5, ages 6 to 12) that includes a coin with a hidden code.
When you redeem the code online, your child gets enough credits at the Penguin Club store for two items.
These could include roller skates or a Puffle pet toy.
Slightly larger than the pig in your toothbrush, Hexbug Nano ($10, for 5 years and older) is the latest in a line of button-battery-powered microrobots.
The fake bug moves quickly on 12 vibrating silicone legs, in random directions.
It's fun to make a maze of blocks to see if you can find the exit.
It's also durable.
Ours was able to leave the kitchen table and even spend some time inside our dog's mouth.
A more moderate side of law enforcement in China is being promoted
As an urban instructor sergeant, Tang Shenbin made his way into a city square, severely inspecting the nervous people in his charge, issuing orders in a low voice with military authority.
He wanted the female members of chengguan, China's stocky urban police, feared and despised for their capricious forceful measures and their penchant for violence, to convey a certain impression to a handful of onlookers.
"Firmly!"
"Attention!"
Show them, he whispered, "how pretty girls are!"
Four girls who barely made it through their teens in white gloves and identical olive green jackets and tight pants to get attention.
Four pairs of perfectly aligned black shoes.
Four elegant hats perfectly placed on top of the hair tied with blue and white striped bowls.
"Personally, I think they have a normal appearance", said Mr. Tang, disdainfully.
"The models are cute".
More than one government has tried to clean up the image of China's city inspectors.
A city ordered that all new recruits have a bachelor's degree.
Guangdong Province changed the grayish green color of the uniforms to a supposedly more attractive blue.
Wuhan, in central China, replaced the use of force with intimidating looks: In 2009, according to one report, 50 officers surrounded a wayward snack cart, and watched it frown constantly for half an hour, until the street vendor packed up his things and left.
Xindu, an urban district of 680,000 in Chengdu, has chosen a radical makeover.
Since 2003, the district has added 13 women to its urban police force, specifically chosen for their appearance, proportion and youth.
The idea is to give the rough cop a softer, more feminine side.
Sadly, even Scarlett Johansson would have to fight to increase China's meager respect for these city squads.
And for good reason, critics would argue.
Unlike the police, these officers are only authorized to enforce city ordinances, imposing fines and other administrative penalties.
But the Chinese news media routinely portray a different reality.
In January 2008, inspectors in Hubei Province beat a passerby to death after he used his cell phone to film them dispersing a protest against a landfill.
Last year, a training manual for Beijing inspectors was stolen and posted online, describing how to effectively whip offenders without causing them to bleed.
This year, a watermelon street vendor in Shanghai suffered brain damage after a fight with five officers.
A violent video game, available for download online, features Chinese-trained inspectors attacking street vendors.
"Chengguan has left a scar on the government", lamented China Daily, a national publication, last year after another controversy over tactics.
The newspaper called for "a really thorough cleanup".
Skeptics say the current approach is far from this.
After the district asked for eight new female recruits through a notice in October, an editorial in The Beijing Evening News asked whether the women had real duties or were simply a stage distraction.
The answer seems to be a little bit of both.
The district's notice called for female candidates, ages 18 to 22, with a good figure "and the five harmonious facial features".
They must have been above average height, over five feet, two and a half inches.
Retirement at the age of 26 is compulsory.
Officials said the work was too physically demanding for women over 25.
"Your image is the important thing", an anonymous district official told Rednet.com, a quasi-government website.
"First, the external qualities of the candidates will determine whether they meet the requirements, such as height, weight, facial features, etc".
Then comes temperament "and the qualities within".
Female chengguan are like florists, he said, adding, "in addition to being florists, they will have other responsibilities".
Zheng Lihua, deputy director of the district's city administration office, is not eager to endorse that description.
But he noted that height requirements were standard in many Chinese job ads for both sexes.
Then comes the demand for harmonious facial features.
If that means being handsome, it's a matter of debate among the Chinese.
Surely, the handicapped or disfigured should not show up.
"We cannot allow a lame person or a hunchback to come to work here", Mr. Zheng said.
"Your image would not be good".
Liu Yi, who patrols Baoguang Square near a monastery, is 22 years old, with his red cheeks and a subtly curved mouth.
She doesn't think the accent on her looks is sexist, she said.
"Do you think I look sexy in this uniform?" she asked with a sardonic look.
His dimple colleague, 21-year-old Xu Yang, said, "Our work should present the image of the city".
They also don't object to their time-bound work, they said, because they harbor career ambitions greater than simply chasing salespeople off the alleys where they're supposed to circumscribe their business.
Every morning, the squad faces about a dozen street vendors who launch themselves on foot or by bicycle, trying to sell as many buns or bowls of tofu as possible before being thrown out.
"Mr. Wang, you have to leave".
"We've told you many times!" said Ms. Xu as a vendor fled on foot, temporarily abandoning his bicycle cart with noodle trimmings.
Officers describe their duties as more monotonous than exhausting.
"This is pretty much the same thing every day", said 20-year-old Huang Jing, who studies marketing in his spare time.
"Very routine".
One reason is that female officers lack the power of their male counterparts to confiscate merchandise from vendors.
They can only threaten to report offenders to their male supervisors.
This tends to protect them from the sudden public displays of animosity against bureaucracy, which are common throughout China.
This year, hundreds of citizens in Kunming, the capital of Yunnan province, rioted after a false rumor spread that Chengguan officers had killed a salesman.
More than a dozen Chengguan police or officers were injured in the nighttime incident; 14 government vehicles were overturned or set on fire.
For the moment Xindu has avoided such violence.
But calm is hardly guaranteed.
Just two blocks from the peaceful Baoguang Square, where the female officers patrolled that morning, more than 50 people gathered in a corner.
Officers had seized a motorcycle that was being repaired on the sidewalk instead of in a shop, as required by regulation.
The owner of the motorcycle was screaming roughly.
