The senator's lawyers announced Wednesday that Justice Department prosecutors have exonerated Senator John Ensign of criminal charges stemming from his affair with a former campaign assistant and his efforts to secure work by lobbying for the woman's husband.
The decision ends the most serious legal threat facing Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was considered a possible Republican presidential candidate for 2012, until the scandal over his affair made national headlines last year and hurt his career.
Ensign's office said it was "surely pleased" by the decision, which came after a year-long investigation.
The senator could still face disciplinary action from the Senate Ethics Committee.
Ensign's attorneys said the Justice Department had "informed us that Senator Ensign is no longer a target of its investigation and that it has no plans to bring charges against him on this matter".
The Justice Department declined to comment on the case.
The announcement came as a surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Justice Department, who said there appeared to be significant evidence to indicate that Ensign may have conspired to violate a federal criminal ban on lobbying.
Interviews, email and other documents first leaked in October 2009 in The New York Times indicated that Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his aides, obtain lucrative work through lobbying, to silence Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the senator's affair with her.
Mrs. Hampton once worked as treasurer for an Ensign campaign.
Ensign contacted several political sponsors to find Mr. Hampton work and advocated on their behalf after they had hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them, according to the documents and interviews.
As Hampton had recently been an Ensign's aide, he was barred by law from lobbying for his former employer or the Senate for a year.
Ethics experts said the unusual arrangement between Ensign and Hampton, who were close friends before the affair, appeared to be at odds with the so-called "revolving door lobbying ban", which seeks to restrict former state employees from using their connections for personal business.
From the evidence that has been made public, "it appeared to be a prima facie case of a conspiracy to substantially violate the revolving door statute", said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending clients under investigation by the government.
While Justice Department officials declined to explain the reasoning behind the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said the department appeared wary of accepting political prosecutions after several major setbacks to its public integrity section, including last year's decision to drop prosecution against former Senator Ted Stevens amid charges of procedural misconduct.
Federal prosecutors "are clearly cowards", said Melanie Sloan, executive director of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, an advocacy group that brought several complaints against Ensign in the case.
"This basically means that high-ranking government officials can now assume that the laws do not apply to them", he added.
Paul Coggins, Ensign's lead attorney, said in an interview that he received a phone call from a Justice Department prosecutor on Monday and another call the next day, telling him the department did not want to press charges against his client.
Ensign's defense team had been cooperating with prosecutors in an attempt to persuade them that the senator, as his office reiterated in a statement Wednesday, "acted in accordance with the law".
Coggins refused to explain in detail the legal arguments he gave to the prosecutors.
"I'm not comfortable going into details about my discussions with the Justice Department, I can only say that we think they made the right decision", he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to reverse an investigation into a separate complaint by the ethics group, which alleges that a $96,000 payment from Ensign's parents to the Hamptons violated federal election law.
The election commission said they didn't have enough evidence to prove the money was nothing more than a gift.
Energy NV is a major Nevada company that had long supported the senator, which got a job through lobbying thanks to Ensign's help with Hampton.
