Can civility build a bridge to bridge the divides?
After a remarkable campaign of invective and negativity, a little civility has been unleashed in Washington this week.
Is this a harbinger of genuine future bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before a quick return to partisan fighting in the capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders produced no progress on the major issues to be addressed during the outgoing session.
But from what everyone says, it was at least a polite discussion about the differences between the two sides, as well as a recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another empty episode to gain partisan points.
Wednesday's public meeting of the chairman's deficit committee was equally civilised, despite the political differences that remain among the members.
It seems clear that the close interaction over a period of months generated a mutual respect that transcends the ideological divide that still separates the members.
That is hardly enough to declare a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Now both sides are in a testing period, probing each other for signs of cooperation and compromise, as they try to gauge the limits of public opinion and voters' patience for a renewed partisan war.
That's why the meeting on Tuesday and subsequent evaluations by the participants were made with minimal demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too big and too deeply rooted to suggest any rapid climate change that existed over the past two years.
Whether it's taxes, expenses, health care or welfare, the two sides are at opposite poles.
Anyway, the November election has softened the mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
"There's no question that things have changed with regard to the way things are said", said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
"They're inevitable after the election.
Elections arouse partisan passions, which then fade away.
That's good".
On some issues, particularly those on the agenda for the outgoing session, the Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax cuts are due at the end of the year, and nobody's in favor of this.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or all of the reductions, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, there is likely to be a compromise to expand unemployment benefits, probably because Republicans cannot make it seem that they are in favor of tax cuts for the rich, denying unemployment benefits to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting at the White House, there is increased optimism for a possible deal on these issues during the outgoing session, along with the ratification of the new START (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty) nuclear disarmament pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on the pressing issues of the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to continued bipartisanship when the new 112th Congress meets in January.
He said, on the contrary, that it was very likely and even inevitable that a period of disagreement would begin.
"After the things that need to be done are done, in the short term psychology will reverse the situation to one of confrontation", he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism (which is widely shared) about the fact that civicism can lead to true cooperation.
"I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as a rehearsal for the main event of 2012", he said.
The reasons have a lot to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and the Tea Party voters, who contributed decisively to its creation.
As much as Republican leaders are aware of the dangers of overstating their position, they know they must try to fulfill their promises to cut state spending and repeal the new health care law.
These partisan lines are already clearly seen in the initial reactions to the deficit committee's recommendations, which include reforming the tax code and raising some taxes and the retirement age, and cutting spending.
Co-chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, in their own estimation, have forced the deficit issue onto the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes on the 18-member committee to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and they've been struggling to get anywhere near that number.
The greatest resistance is among elected officials on the panel, suggesting that in tax matters there is, at least currently, little basis or desire for compromise.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between the Republicans in the White House and those in Congress.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan clashes, when Republicans challenge Obama on the budget, taxes and health care, followed by a period of increased bipartisan cooperation.
What would bring about change?
The public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the partisanship of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties work together.
If the confrontation leads to a stalemate, as it did in 1995, then both parties will watch the reaction of the people closely.
Anyone who considers themselves losing will probably change course and seek compromise.
However, this can be an optimistic view.
Partisanship and polarization are higher today than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a larger ideological gap between Obama and congressional Republicans than there was between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as merely the prelude to a more momentous election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civility shown this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
A leaked US document portrays Moscow as a haven for corruption
The control of the city is in the hands of a "kleptocracy", and it leaves a portion of the bribes and protection money it collects directly to the Kremlin, the US Embassy in Russia reported in February.
It was reported that both the police and the Federal Security Service operate huge blackmail systems, which helps explain the high cost of living in Moscow.
They raise money not only from legitimate businesses but also from organized criminal groups.
Every layer of the bureaucracy, what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called "vertical authority", takes its toll as money climbs the ladder.
The note, which was sent to Washington under the name Ambassador John Beyrle, was published by WikiLeaks on its website on Wednesday.
The note is based on sources whose names have been redacted.
It was written while Yuri Luzhkov was still mayor of Moscow, and it blames him for much of the corruption.
President Dmitry Medvedev fired him in October, but there has been little evidence of a purge since.
Luzhkov and his wife, Yelena Baturina, who owns a major construction company, have consistently denied corruption allegations over the years, and he has won several libel lawsuits over such allegations.
In September, when asked on a Russian TV channel about a documentary that suggested he was corrupt, he stated: "It's crazy, it's bullshit, it's annoying".
According to polls, Russians overwhelmingly believe that their society is corrupt.
But it is unusual to find details explained in detail, as they were in the embassy report, and it is unheard of for diplomats from a foreign country to do that.
"The direct links of the Moscow city government to crime have led some to call it 'dysfunctional,' and to claim that the government functions more like a kleptocracy than a government", the note states.
"Criminal elements enjoy a 'krysha' (a mafia and criminal term that literally means 'roof' or protection) that goes through the police, the Federal Security Service (SFS), the Ministry of Internal Affairs (MVD), and the prosecutor's office, as well as all sectors of the bureaucracy of the Moscow city government.
"Analysts identify a three-tiered structure in the criminal world of Moscow".
"Luzhkov is at the top".
"The SFS, the MVD and the militia are on the second level".
"Finally, common criminals and corrupt inspectors are at the lowest level".
"This is an inefficient system in which criminal groups fill a void in some areas, because the city does not provide some services".
The report claims that the SFS collects money from the larger companies, and that the police target the smaller shops.
One source, the report stated, "explained that Moscow business owners understand that it is best to get protection from the MVD and SFS (rather than from organized crime groups) since they not only have more weapons, resources and power than criminal groups, but are also protected by law".
"For this reason, protection against criminal gangs is no longer a priority".
The note notes that while the money collection is complete, protection can be irregular; even those who pay are subject to arrest.
Those who do not pay quickly find their businesses closed for one reason or another.
Medvedev has spoken several times about the fight against corruption, but has admitted that little progress has been made.
The embassy note reports men taking suitcases, probably full of cash, inside the Kremlin itself.
"In his fight against corruption, Medvedev has to trust the bureaucrats", Georgy Satarov, head of the Indem think tank in Moscow, said in a recent interview.
"But he's a part of this bureaucracy".
"He does not belong to a political class, because there is no longer a political class in Russia".
Without politics, without opposition, without separation of powers, he said, corruption is inevitable.
On a national scale, Indem estimates that corruption costs Russia more than $300 billion a year.
In a recent survey of global perceptions of corruption conducted by the nongovernmental organization Transparency International, the country was ranked 154th (countries are ranked from least to most corrupt).
The revelation of the US Embassy note, which didn't happen until late at night Moscow time, will surely cause displeasure within the Russian government, and even though Luzhkov can be blamed for Moscow's weaknesses, it could be an opportunity for the Kremlin to argue that it is fixing the problem.
Interviewed for CNN by Larry King, Putin suggested that the WikiLeaks documents might be lies and reacted angrily to a revelation that claimed U.S. diplomats called him Batman and Medvedev Robin.
"The truth of the matter is that this is related to our interaction, which is an important factor of domestic policies in this country", he said.
"But to be honest with you, we did not suspect that this would have been done with such arrogance, with such pressure and, you know, that it would be done in such an immoral manner".
Khmer Rouge veterans forced to face the past
In a dimly lit concrete classroom, with stained and peeled walls, the principal of Anlong Veng High School remembered the man who built it, the last leader of the Khmer Rouge Ta Mok.
"Everyone here loves Ta Mok".
"He was a good leader and cared about his people", said 42-year-old Sreng Kor Ma.
Known as "the Butcher" for his brutality during Khmer Rouge rule, the commander remains popular in this remote former Khmer Rouge stronghold in northwestern Cambodia, where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure, and where thousands of former Khmer Rouge soldiers still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered to the government, long-held loyalty is finally being challenged in Anlong Veng.
In April, a local truth and reconciliation forum allowed victims to publicly confront people who had participated in the regime.
In June, the government distributed a high school textbook here that for the first time teaches the history of the Khmer Rouge to the children of its former soldiers.
And in July, a joint UN-Cambodian court issued the first conviction of a former Khmer Rouge member, sentencing the former head of the notorious Tuol Sleng torture center, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Duch, to 35 years in prison.
With each of these events, anxiety has grown among the Khmer Rouge veterans of Anlong Veng, complicating reconciliation efforts and their attempts to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
"There is resentment and fear among the former Khmer Rouge, but they can't do anything", said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodia Documentation Center, an independent organization that researches the regime.
"For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil".
"This is creating divisions within families".
During the Khmer Rouge rule of Cambodia, between 1975 and 1979, approximately 1.7 million people were executed or died of hunger, disease or overwork.
When in 1979 the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the Pol Pot-led government, the remnants of the regime and its military fled to Cambodia's border with Thailand.
There they launched an insurrection that lasted until the last movement surrendered in December 1998.
As Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led guerrilla warfare from their bases in the mountains and jungles of western Cambodia, Ta Mok cultivated followers in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace deal led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began defecting to the government, culminating in the surrender of Ieng Sary in 1996, and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998, and Ta Mok, who had resisted, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the nearby Dangrek Mountains.
He died in a Phnom Penh prison in 2006 while awaiting trial.
Without the support of their benefactors, the longest-serving Khmer Rouge fighters have fallen into the absolute misery that is common in rural Cambodia, and many are nostalgic for the movement.
Although a few elite Khmer Rouge officials retained their local administrative posts in exchange for laying down their arms, the soldiers remain poor and unskilled farmers.
"These people have gained little after the surrender", said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which holds public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
"They have incorporated the regime's utopian agrarian ideology".
"They were raised without any concept of doing business".
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle near Anlong Veng before devoting herself to life as a poor rice farmer in 1998.
"Life with the Khmer Rouge was good", he said.
"Ta Mok fed everyone".
"But now life is difficult because we have to provide for ourselves".
The current Khmer Rouge court has also caused concern here.
Early next year, the court is expected to begin prosecuting Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister.
The court's mandate is to prosecute the main leaders and those most responsible for the crimes, but it has not said whether it will pursue cases beyond those four.
This didn't do much to calm the fears in Anlong Veng.
Recent media speculation has focused on Im Chaem, 64, who was a district chief in Banteay Meanchey province during Khmer Rouge rule in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told researchers at the Cambodia Documentation Center that she had overseen the construction of the Trapeang Thma dam, a project in which thousands of forced laborers are thought to have died.
On a recent humiliating afternoon, Im Chaem returned home from working in the fields on wooden piles on a dirt road outside Anlong Veng.
As the sun cast long shadows over the dry grass, Im Chaem refused to talk about his past in the Khmer Rouge.
She said that if the court summoned her she would not appear.
"Cambodia is at peace and stable", he said.
"If there are more prosecutions, there will be war".
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who defected from the Khmer Rouge in 1978, has also repeatedly warned of instability if the court prosecutes more suspects, although experts and historians question this.
"Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past", he said.
But facing the past is precisely what Cambodia needs to do to move forward, said Chhang Youk of the documentation center.
"Reconciliation, according to the Khmer, is putting the broken pieces back together", he said.
"It is our duty to put these broken pieces together so that we can understand".
The center produced the first government-approved textbook on the Khmer Rouge, called "A History of Democratic Kampuchea", 75 pages long.
It was distributed in Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the Ministry of Education's high school history textbook, which contains less than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
As in most of Cambodia, young people in Anlong Veng know little about Khmer Rouge, despite the city's ties to the regime.
Toque Valeak, 19, a student at Anlong Veng High School, said the new textbook helped students understand an important part of their story.
But his parents reacted with skepticism when he took the book home to study.
"My family rejects many parts of the textbook and the court", he said.
"They are suspicious because they are not sure how many people the court will prosecute".
Such resistance has made the reconciliation process complex and difficult, Sok Leang said.
But the public forums, the textbook and the court are starting to make an impact, he said.
Anyway, here the Khmer Rouge retain a powerful charm.
In the Dangrek Mountains, a path with too much weed and covered with discarded plastic bags leads to a rectangle of black soot covered by a rusty tin roof.
Pol Pot's body was burned here on a pile of tires after his death in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, 31, a cell phone salesman on the side of the road, said he didn't know much about the man who was cremated there.
"But he has a strong spirit and many locals go there to pray for him", she said.
It was Nuom Sothea's birthday, and later that day she decided to walk to Pol Pot's final resting place, where she would leave a bunch of ripe bananas in the hope of good luck.
