Red Bull wins F1 with a secret weapon from Siemens
Software designs improvements to cars in real time.
Since Red Bull burst into the world of Formula 1 in 2004, its history in this select universe of speed has been marked by surprise and success.
At first no one took into consideration the options of a newly arrived team and, despite the upward trajectory of the last seasons, last November, in the final straight of the championship everyone bet on the triumph of Fernando Alonso's Ferrari.
Without belittling the driving skills of the eventual champion, Sebastian Vettel, nor the power of the Renault engine that powers his car, the "secret weapon" that the multinational Siemens has put in Red Bull's hands to make it a winning team has become a legend in the world of Formula 1.
It is in fact a powerful process simulation software that the German company put on the market in 2007 for purposes far removed from high-level automotive competition.
Called PLM, this powerful computer tool has been used to design assembly lines of manufacturing plants around the world, power plants, high-precision instruments.
The aim is to reproduce, simulate faithfully the product or process before building it in real life, thus avoiding failures and avoidable costs.
PLM has facilitated the development of Canon cameras, Sukhoi aircraft and Nissan's most famous utility cars.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of Siemens' industrial division, explains that the use of this computer instrument in its Formula 1 factory has allowed Red Bull to design and implement "in a few hours, almost in real time", the modifications, changes and improvements detected during races and testing.
Russwurm explains that teams in 1992 had an average of 10 technicians in their team who were able to introduce a maximum of three or four improvements to the vehicles during each season.
The Red Bull team now has 180 highly qualified young professionals who, equipped with powerful computer equipment, analyse and design all kinds of modifications to the cars.
The Siemens manager explained that the PLM software is capable of analysing and improving all the elements of Red Bull's racing cars except the engine, which is the sole responsibility of Renault.
Materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety features are modified.
Changes can be made from simulator to virtual reality in less than 24 hours, thanks to advanced laser and high-tech autoclave production systems.
The only limitation to this madness of technological improvement is the figure of 40 million dollars that each Formula 1 team can spend at most each season to facilitate the competition.
Red Bull has set up the high-tech factory to design and produce its cars in a town about 30 miles from London.
These are two buildings that are restricted to visitors, especially journalists.
Everything that happens there is considered "top secret".
The staff for this task is 580 people, including its two drivers, champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
The hero of Red Bull Formula One, without a doubt, is the recent champion Sebastian Vetell.
Among the immense technological resources that the energy drink brand has put at the service of its participation in the circuits, there are other protagonists whose competition is invaluable and their notoriety is zero.
The factory's chief technology officer, Steve Nevey, says that five years ago it was safe to say that R&D advances in wagon cars accounted for 50 percent of victories and the drivers were responsible for the rest.
Today, these percentages have varied and technology accounts for 85% of success, while pilots contribute 15% of added value.
Nevey acknowledges that Vettel or Webber will never be replaced by computers as "they are unpredictable gladiators".
