Shoe and the German red line
Berlin has chosen to remain in the euro, but it has set the conditions for the whole Union.
The tensions in the markets have led to a twofold government response.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has advanced new adjustment measures, from tax cuts to SMEs, regulation of private placement agencies or the abolition of the 426 euros of unemployment benefits, to the privatization of 49% of AENA, the management of the airports of Barajas and El Prat and 30% of State Lotteries.
On the other hand, vice-president Elena Salgado, with the support of former president Felipe González, has joined the criticism of chancellor Angela Merkel for her responsibility in unleashing the current crisis.
How are these movements to be interpreted?
Go ahead, Merkel's position is not a mistake in her communication policy.
On the contrary, it is another twist in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
And here Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which clashes with the old traditions of many of its partners.
In the face of European resistance, Germany is beginning to speculate on three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first, a strong euro, made up of itself, Austria and the Netherlands, among other countries, while the south would leave the currency area.
The second is the recovery of the framework, although it now seems like science fiction, with a very favourable opinion, close to 50% of the population.
The third is a redesign of the euro, in line with German proposals for greater macroeconomic control, budgetary rigor, fines for countries that have failed, possible suspensions of payments for some of them and the extension of the costs of potential adjustments to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been defined for some time, so there are no excuses now.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission were stimulating deficits, the German government got out of hand a constitutional reform to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first sign of a divergence between what Germany believed needed to be done (fiscal austerity plans and stability in public finances) and what its European partners, including France, were doing.
The second blow was given by the Central European country when Merkel painfully prolonged the rescue decision for Greece.
It was already the subject of fierce criticism at the time, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public and published opinion were very much against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel again emerged with a clear position, demanding reform of the Union's Treaties, to make it possible to save a country and at the same time force private lenders to bear part of the cost.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, because it has precipitated the Irish crisis and everything else.
But his proposal, albeit a little sweetened, has been approved and in the coming months we should be witnessing the process of reforming the Union to make those measures possible from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
And he is telling us all that, even if we have to take measures now that he may not agree with, by that date the old way of working of the euro will be over.
The year 2013 will mark the birth of a new monetary area, in which countries that break the rules will be severely sanctioned, may be forced to declare a suspension of payments and, in that case, the private sector will also bear part of the cost.
Germany is telling us that we must pursue a severe growth path with high savings and investment rates, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness and positive external balances.
Another alternative based on debt and construction, with huge holes in the balance of payments, like the one that has presided over Spanish growth in the boom years, they simply will not tolerate.
The invitation is clear.
And we'd be wrong not to understand.
