Sports and law fraud
Tricks like Alonso and Ramos against Ajax show ingenuity but not willingness to escape a penalty.
The allegedly planned expulsion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) from the November 23 match against Ajax in the Champions League has caused rivers of ink to be written about whether or not such behaviour is unsportsmanlike and whether, eventually, both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, with only a few minutes to go in the game (which their team had clearly won), the two players deliberately wasted time in making fouls to cause the referee to show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid will finish as group leaders, both players will meet the regulatory sanction in the next match of the league, against Auxerre, and can go through clean of cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA disciplinary committee has sanctioned the team's coach, Jose Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
Provoking a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, but rather common in the world of football.
It's so widespread that it's part of the ethos, the unwritten but followed rules of this sport.
Part of the debate in the case is due to the fact that it was played by a team from the Real Madrid team (which in its anthem boasts of nobility and honor, and which in past occasions has fined its players for similar acts) and the dramatization orchestrated, apparently, by Mourinho, who adds another episode to his long history of being a histrionic and provocative coach.
In any case, the debate is about whether this type of behaviour, which is not expressly prohibited by the regulations, is contrary to the principles of sport, that is, whether these actions are a fraud of the law; indeed, they are actions that respect the rules of the sport, but they seem to elude their meaning.
The question is whether they are damaging the spirit of sport.
One of the assets of the sporting spirit is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that was not endangered by these actions, that is, there was no violent game.
Another of these goods that is referred to as fair play is to prevent the team of the offending players from taking unfair advantage of the opposing team, which also did not happen.
The paradox of the action of the Real Madrid players is that they did not conform to what we normally characterise as cheating or law fraud, as their violation of the rules was not done in secret to try to avoid the penalty, but precisely their action tried to be the most obvious to receive the punishment of the referee.
They waited and gladly accepted the penalty.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders gain from the willful misconduct examined.
It seems necessary to note here that neither the opponent is put at a disadvantage nor is there any advantage in the same match, since the result of the action is obviously to leave the team with fewer players.
And it's not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club won't be able to count on those players.
The advantage, obviously, is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indeterminacy, because the team can be eliminated at the first of the change, and in addition with this action the players fulfill a penalty match and go to the second cycle of cards, in which the suspension by accumulation of cards occurs with one less than in the first cycle.
So, going round and round, it's not so clear that it's an advantage.
In short, these actions are not against the spirit of sport, which is to make strategic decisions to make the most of what the rules allow.
In the case at hand, the players did not act to evade the application of the penalty (this would be a clear case of law fraud), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without escaping or escaping punishment.
Although the line between ingenuity and legal fraud is blurred, this time I think it was a clear case of ingenuity.
The controversy, I think, arises from two factors: because there were two self-expulsions and because of the way in which the directive to provoke them was transmitted.
The damage done to the principles of sport by these actions is not so much ethical as aesthetic.
