Pakistan's nuclear program is a major concern in the United States.
Islamabad produces atomic weapons "at a faster rate than any other country".
WikiLeaks leaks confirm the links between the Taliban and Pakistan.
The content of the correspondence between the US embassy in Pakistan and the US State Department leaked by the Wikileaks portal confirms the enormous concerns in Washington about the Pakistani nuclear program.
Apart from the illuminating and juicy details they offer about the content of the talks and the thoughts of the US diplomatic representatives accredited in Islamabad, the documents reveal that cooperation between the two countries on nuclear security, instead of increasing, is "declining", and that the unstable Asian country is producing nuclear weapons "at a faster rate than any other country in the world".
The particularity of Pakistan's nuclear programme - that the weapons are not assembled but are stored in parts to make it difficult to destroy them in the event of an attack - is one of the main reasons for alarm in Washington.
So says Ambassador to Pakistan Anne W. Patterson in a report prior to the visit of then-National Security Advisor James Jones: "The proximity of some nuclear facilities to territory under Taliban attack, the rumored dispersal of nuclear materials, and the vulnerability of transporting atomic materials".
The high number of people involved in nuclear arsenals and missile programmes is seen, not only by the US but also by Russia, as proliferating and a reason to keep watch.
"Pakistan has had to hire personnel with strict religious beliefs to protect nuclear facilities; given the fall in educational and cultural standards, extremist organizations have more opportunities to recruit people to work on nuclear or missile programs", Russian Foreign Ministry expert Yuri Korolev said at a meeting with his US counterparts.
The most recent documentation leaked by Julian Assange's portal is the declining cooperation between the US and Pakistan on nuclear proliferation issues and the high pace of Pakistani nuclear weapons production.
An embassy dispatch in May, calling communication with Pakistan "frustrating", said: "Transparency is often lacking; offers of aid go unanswered or are dismissed".
In another message, Peter Lavoy, a National Intelligence official for South Asia, notes that "despite the economic catastrophe, Pakistan is producing nuclear weapons at a faster rate than any other country in the world".
Ambassador Patterson also asks Washington, during a visit by the army chief, General Ashfaq Kayani, to make "very clear" to the official that "the Pakistani army must end tacit support for terrorist groups".
To the hunt for the head of Wikileaks
Obama appoints a top counterterrorism official to prevent further leaks.
Interpol is issuing a red alert in order to track the movements and locate Assange wherever he is.
Everything about WikiLeaks and its founder, Julian Assange, forms a complicated maze where it's hard to be certain about the facts.
Yesterday Interpol issued a "red alert" to "locate and track Assange's movements".
However, this is not a traditional arrest warrant.
It is not new, it dates from November 20.
And it's not about the latest leak of over a quarter of a million US diplomatic documents but about the sexual abuse allegations the Australian faces in Sweden.
In addition, the lawyer for the creator of Wikileaks, Mark Stephens, says that "the police know where and how to contact Mr Assange".
It was on the 20th when the international police force based in Lyon (France) issued the order at the request of Sweden, but did not reveal it until yesterday, after receiving permission from the authorities of that country.
As it stands, all 188 countries of Interpol have indications to identify or locate Assange "with a view to his provisional arrest and extradition".
Although Interpol cannot order the arrest of an individual affected by a red alert, many of the member countries, the organization has explained, do consider the so-called red notice a free-way to proceed with an arrest - which must be undertaken by the national police force - especially if they have a bilateral extradition agreement, as is the case in Sweden and England, where Assange is believed to be.
The move has angered Assange's lawyers, who yesterday published a letter denouncing that the 39-year-old WikiLeaks founder has been willing to answer questions from Swedish authorities via videoconference.
They also recall that Assange requested and obtained permission to leave Sweden from the prosecutor of his case, whom they compare to the mythical Lavrentiy Pavlovich Beria, Stalin's head of security.
"This seems like a hunt, not a legal persecution", the letter says.
While the world searches for him - and his mother from Australia defends her son's innocence - Assange remains in the dark, but not silent.
On Monday, he gave an interview to the editor of Time magazine via Skype from an undisclosed location, a conversation in which he asked for the resignation of US Secretary of State Hillary Clinton.
"If it can be shown that he was responsible for ordering American diplomats to spy on the UN in violation of international treaties that the US has signed, he should resign", he said.
His opinion was denounced yesterday by White House press secretary Robert Gibbs, who called the resignation request "ridiculous and absurd".
"I'm not entirely sure why we should care about the opinion of a guy with a website", he told CNN.
Obama himself has tasked a senior counterterrorism official, Russell Travers, to prevent further leaks of documents.
President Barack Obama's spokesman's attempt to play down Assange contrasts with the views these days proclaimed by conservative politicians and commentators.
Peter King, the congressman who will chair the House Homeland Security Committee in January, has asked the State Department to consider including Wikileaks on the terrorist list "to intervene and fund and prosecute anyone who gives them any contribution or help".
Even further has gone Tom Flanagan, an adviser to Canadian President Stephen Harper, who has had to retract after saying Assange should be "killed".
"Obama should target him and use a drone or something".
The one who did not apologize was Mike Huckabee, a Baptist minister, former governor of Arkansas and a possible presidential candidate.
"Whoever in the government leaked the information is guilty of treason and anything other than execution would be too kind of a punishment", he declared on Fox.
