China maintains targets to reduce greenhouse gases
The representative of that country at COP16 said his country has made enormous efforts to reduce the carbon footprint and said he supports its offer to reduce by 2020 between 40 and 45 percent its emission of greenhouse gases.
China is still committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, said Su Wei, China's representative at COP16.
In his first public appearance at the 16th Conference of the Parties to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (COP16), Su Wei said his country has made huge efforts to reduce its carbon footprint and to reconvert its industry.
In fact, he said, over the past four years his country has invested $245 million in efforts to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
However, he made it clear that China will not change its objectives but will continue to work together with the international community on this matter.
He said China's climate change strategy is divided into four areas: dialogue, capacity building, institution building and support for pilot programmes.
In all these areas progress has been made, including the approval last year of a new Energy Law, which includes the objectives set for reducing emissions of gases, he explained.
On the other hand, he stressed that in China, the federal authorities have been working in a coordinated manner with state and local authorities, to achieve the goals of energy saving, efficient energy use and emission reduction.
In addition, there are numerous multiannual plans, both financed by the Chinese government and by governments in other countries, which are under way or have already been completed.
For example, he mentioned the Energy Efficiency Programme, which was implemented over the past five years and received investments from the United Nations (UN), the government and the private sector.
A provincial project on climate change is also underway, another for the change of incandescent lamps by savers and another one of mitigation and adaptation, he said.
At the same table, Martin Krol, the government's scientific adviser on climate change, said China's efforts have been greater than generally thought.
For example, he said, per capita greenhouse gas emissions in China are six tons per person, while in the United States they are 100 tons; China is responsible for 9 percent of the historical contribution to pollution.
It has also made unprecedented efforts in energy use, such as increasing energy efficiency by 20 percent in the last five years and plans to do more by 2020, he said.
