US changes visa rules
You should go to the Visa Applicant Service before your interview at the Consular Section; the cost and waiting time will be less.
As of January 10, 2011, the visa process at the U.S. Embassy and Consulate will change.
Under the new procedure, most applicants will have to go to the Visa Applicant Service (ASC) before their interview at the Consular Section.
The ASC staff will take the applicant's biometric information, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section before the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for applicants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, no longer needing to make a payment for the appointment, another payment for processing the visa application and another payment for the courier service to deliver the document.
The applicant will only make a one-off payment covering all three services.
The current fee will remain unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa cases with a request (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for business and investor visas.
Persons wishing to renew their visa will not have to attend an interview with the Consular Officer, but will only have to go to the nearest ASC where they will present their documents and have their fingerprints taken.
Because biometric information will be taken at the ASC, applicants who require a second appointment to be interviewed at the Consular Section will stay in the Consular Section for less time than in the past.
Likewise, those who apply for visas at the Consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of 26 dollars.
For further information on the new visa application procedure, please visit the following page: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
