The National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) will announce an astrobiological discovery Thursday that could prove the theory that extraterrestrial life does exist.
The find will be presented at a press conference tomorrow, Thursday, at 1:00 p.m. at NASA headquarters in Washington by experts in astrobiology, a science described as the study of the origin, evolution, distribution and future of life in the Universe.
Citing the press, NASA said it would present "a finding that will impact the search for extraterrestrial life", prompting speculation from experts in other countries.
The discovery could prove the theory that there are creatures just like us in hostile environments that were once thought uninhabitable, and it could put on the table the possibility that they could become intelligent beings like humans if they improve the conditions in which they live.
It appears to be a microbe that was found at the bottom of Mono Lake in Yosemite National Park, California, where it lives in an environment that was thought to be too poisonous for any life form, since the lake is rich in arsenic.
Somehow, the creature uses arsenic as a way to survive and this ability increases the possibility that similar life could exist on other planets, which do not have our beneficial atmosphere.
According to astrobiologists, if these organisms use arsenic in their metabolism, it will be shown that "there is another form of life, a second form of life, different from the one we know".
The space agency will announce the true scope of the findings at a press conference tomorrow, Thursday.
The conference will be attended by geobiologist Pamela Conrad, who studies the possibility of life on Mars; and biologist Steven Benner, one of the scientists who study Titan (Saturn's largest moon), under the perspective that its chemistry is similar to that of the Earth.
