A Worldwide Plan to Renew Lighting
Yesterday, the UN proposed in Cancun a plan to renew domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in a hundred countries to reduce greenhouse gases (GHG) by an amount that corresponds to almost a third of the additional decrease that must be made to stabilize the planet's climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is part of the series of major concrete projects that the UN hopes to adopt in Cancun to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments in the industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if incandescent bulbs, which still monopolise between 50 and 70 percent of the market, were replaced by fluorescent bulbs or, even better, by light emitting diode (LED) bulbs, much of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GHG emitted on the planet to light humans would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
It is equivalent to 70% of the emissions of the global car fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, the major emitter countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that were to reduce global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, 5 Gt of this amount should be reduced to stabilise the temperature rise by 2°C by 2020 to prevent it from spiraling out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated as heat and the remaining 5%, that is, produces light.
In the case of fluorescent light bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with the new LED light bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by an additional twofold.
Fluoride light bulbs last an average of between 6,000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched this week by the manufacturer Philips (a company which also participated in the UN study), have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, which gives us an idea of the savings that can be achieved with the replacement plan that would be implemented in 100 countries.
These new bulbs can also run on rheostats and emit very little heat.
On top, they don't contain any mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations about fluorescent bulbs, since they contain mercury and must be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless manufacturers put instructions on them.
However, the report says, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not fluorescent bulbs but coal-fired power plants, which emit a large amount of mercury to produce the electricity that is wasted on incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, such plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury a year.
The report details the advantages that this international programme would offer to each country.
For example, Indonesia would save $1 billion a year in electricity and 8 million tons of CO2, the equivalent of 3.5 billion dollars in thermal power plants.
