Avenging hackers and diligent spies
The WikiLeaks affair has a double value.
On the one hand, it reveals an apparent scandal, a scandal which only seems scandalous in the face of the hypocrisy which governs relations between States, citizens and the press.
It also heralds profound changes on an international scale and foresees a future dominated by regression.
But let's take it one step at a time.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every file created by a secret service (regardless of the nation to which it belongs) is made up exclusively of press clippings.
The "extraordinary" US revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits only reflect what has been written for months in any newspaper (except those belonging to Berlusconi) and Gaddafi's sinisterly ridiculous profile has long given ideas to cabaret artists to create their sketches.
The rule that secret files should only consist of publicly known news is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not just in this century.
If you visit a bookstore devoted to esoteric publications, you will see that each work (about the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rosicrucians) repeats exactly what had been written in the earlier works.
This is not simply because occult writers do not want to do unpublished research (or do not know where to look for novelties about the nonexistent), but because occultists do not simply rely on what they already know, which confirms what they have already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
The same applies to secret files.
The informant is lazy, as is the head of the secret services (if he could not be, I don't know, editor of Libération), who only considers what he can acknowledge to be true.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the US Embassy in Rome was sending to the State Department was the same as the one published by Newsweek the week before.
So why have the revelations of these files caused such a stir?
On the one hand, they are merely saying what every educated person already knows, namely that embassies, at least since the Second World War and since Heads of State can call each other on the telephone or take a plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of some limited representative exercises, have been transformed into spy centres.
Any viewer who watches investigative films knows this perfectly well, we just pretend not to know it out of hypocrisy.
In any case, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad image to American diplomacy.
Second, the idea that any hacker can access the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world seriously affects the prestige of the State Department.
The scandal therefore affects both the victims and the "punishment".
But let's get to the real nature of what happened.
In the old days, in Orwell's time, you could think of yourself as a big brother who controlled every move of his subjects.
Orwell's prophecy has come true since, by being able to control every move through the telephone, every transaction made, hotel visited, highway taken, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it's proven, as it is now, that even the crypts of power's secrets cannot escape a hacker's control, the control relationship ceases to be one-way and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, chosen as the citizens' avenger) can know all the secrets of power.
How can you stand a power that can no longer even keep its own secrets?
It is true, as Georg Simmel said, that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is in fact an empty secret, without a secret, since it comes from the public domain; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks has done, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets means to take away all power.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but it has done, and a lot, to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound inflicted on such a powerful power?
It is clear that in future States will no longer be able to put confidential information online, as it would be like posting it on a street sign.
But it is also clear that with today's technology, you cannot expect to have confidential conversations over the phone.
Nothing is easier than to find out whether and when a Head of State has travelled by air and contacted one of his counterparts.
How can they maintain private and confidential relationships in the future?
I know perfectly well that, at the moment, my forecast is a science fiction and therefore a novel, but I imagine government agents moving discreetly in stagecoaches with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been memorized or, at most, hiding some data written on the heels of their shoes.
That information is then kept, in a single copy, in locked drawers: in the end, the Watergate espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I've written that technology is currently moving forward like a crab, which is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet has re-created a wired telegraph.
Video tapes (analog) had allowed film researchers to study a film step by step, going forward and backward, discovering all the secrets of editing, while now CDs (digital) only allow for moving forward or backward from chapter to chapter, that is, in enormous proportions.
With high-speed trains, we can go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, with the travel it entails, we need three and a half hours.
It is therefore not unusual for politics and communication techniques to lead us back to horse-drawn carriages.
One last comment.
In the old days, the press tried to understand what was going on in secret in embassies.
At present, it is the embassies that ask the press for confidential information.
Climate: France's failures to deliver on its funding promises
One year after the Copenhagen Accord, it is time to examine whether the promises of fast-start financing made by developed countries have been honoured.
And the French tricks have been uncovered.
In the Copenhagen Accord, developed countries committed to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has committed €7.2 billion over three years and France €1.26 billion (i.e. €420 million a year).
At the opening of COP16, the EU put on the table its best cards to convince its partners that its commitment to fast start funding is real: a report detailing the measures taken by its Member States, a press conference, a major accompanying event, the distribution of leaflets...
The transparency operation was appreciated for what it really is: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of accuracy.
The EU announces that it has released €2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to meet its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But if you look at the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
Under the Copenhagen Accord, money must be 'new and additional' to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without prejudice to official development assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the procedure.
Today, each person chooses the reference that suits him best.
For example, the European Commission has taken 2009 as a reference year: international funding is maintained and 150 million are added over three years as fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references for the year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers that the financing of 'all new projects' in 2010 is 'new and additional'.
In other words, there is no reference to expenditure in previous years or to the total level of official development assistance.
In particular, the total amount of French aid to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), as long as it intends to respect its commitment to 'new and additional' funds.
Another crucial element is the distribution between donations and loans.
Again, there is no standard and each person chooses the method of calculation.
Some, such as France, consider that each euro borrowed is equivalent to one euro donated.
Obviously, such a thing is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments which are profitable (often emissions reduction projects based on more efficient technologies), it is a mistake to present a euro to be recovered as equivalent to a euro to be donated.
But France finds such reasoning unhelpful: it 'respects' its €420 million commitment by lending 91.5% (€389.8 million) and donating 8.5% (€36.1 million); see the EU document to see for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union which uses the loan so frequently.
Germany uses 46% of the funds, while Denmark, the Netherlands and Slovakia, among others, meet their commitments with 100% of the funds.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union contributes one euro to meet its commitment, France contributes only ten cents and considers the effort to be comparable.
That's a good trick!
In short, in its fast start financing, France is committing a double abuse: first, in relation to the actions over time and, second, in relation to the actual financial effort.
Spending only 36.1 million euros, it manages to give the impression that it spends 420 million "new and additional", as it had promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that Bercy has been the one who has dealt with the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other member states continue to donate when they can simply lend?) and in the negotiations, since the developing countries are not fools...
The chapter on early finance is a relatively short-term detail in relation to the whole of the climate negotiations.
But it could be just one more grain of sand in the vast machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope not.
Whatever the case, it is essential to learn from this first year of early finance.
First, France could announce a change in its calculation method for 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in line with the other EU countries.
But, in particular, France could advance the debate on the stakes in longterm financing (another key chapter currently being discussed): we will not get rid of the question of the 'additional character' or the method of calculating loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on this issue as it is on others.
We therefore have hope for the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will be arriving in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement on France's fast starts and its view of the 'additional character' and use of loans would help to improve the level of international confidence needed to move forward with the negotiations.
Warning about pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old child ingests 81 different chemicals in a day, according to a study published Wednesday by the association Generations Futures (the ancient movement for the rights and respect of future generations).
The association, which warns that its results "have no statistical significance given the limited number of samples analysed, but are illustrative of the problem", purchased in supermarkets in Oise and Paris between July and September the food that a child of about ten years usually consumes in four meals and a snack a day.
These model meals, which meet official recommendations (five servings of fresh fruit and vegetables, three servings of dairy products and 1.5 litres of water a day), as well as the treats, were tested in laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other contaminants.
The balance sheet is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, 42 classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five classified as safe carcinogens, and 37 substances that may act as endocrine disruptors (EDs), according to studies by institutions such as the International Cancer Research Centre.
"Although the legal limits for each chemical are not exceeded in virtually all cases individually, our study clearly shows that consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic and/or PE contaminants is a concern", the association says.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three considered safe carcinogens, as well as about 20 residues that can damage the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil and intended as a school snack, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to green beans from Kenya, which are used in food, and in which the study has detected traces of a potent insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, Russian steak, canned tuna, and even bread or gum were spiced with pesticides and other chemicals.
In the tap water, the tests revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon slice was the most "nutritious" with 34 chemical residues detected and even the analysis of the plastic plate used to heat the food in the microwave was not completely clean.
The ultimate risk to consumers from these "polluting cocktails" is "likely underestimated", the study says.
The Alliance Europe Ecologie-Les Verts (EE-LV) has proposed a moratorium on the use of pesticides to curb the rise in diseases associated with civilization.
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) indicated the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 in cereals.
